window.TID_SCRIPTS = {"listening-w3-classwork":["PART 1: Student Accommodation Inquiry\n\nAnnouncer | 0:01 This is the IELTS listening test.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:05 You will hear a number of different recordings and you will have to answer questions on what you hear.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:13 There will be time for you to read the instructions and questions and you will have a chance to check your work.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:21 All the recordings will be played once only.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:25 The test is in four parts.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:29 At the end of the test, you will be given 10 minutes to transfer your answers to the answer sheet.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:37 Now, turn to part one.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:44 Part one,\n\nAnnouncer | 0:50 you will hear a student from overseas phoning the student accommodation office of a college in the UK for some information.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:59 First, you have some time to look at questions 1 to 4 on page two.\n\n(Khoảng nghỉ từ 1:01 đến 1:57)\n\nAnnouncer | 1:57 Now we shall begin. You should answer the questions as you listen because you will not hear the recording a second time.\n\nAnnouncer | 2:05 Listen carefully and answer questions 1 to four.\n\nDarren | 2:11 College Accommodation Bureau. Darren speaking. How may I help you?\n\nStudent | 2:16 Oh, good morning. I'm starting at the college in September and I need to find some accommodation.\n\nDarren | 2:22 Right. Well, there are various options.\n\nDarren | 2:26 The first one is to stay in college accommodation. That would be a single room.\n\nStudent | 2:32 How much would that cost?\n\nDarren | 2:34 Well, it depends.\n\nDarren | 2:36 For a standard room, you're looking at £3,276 for the year. That's just for a room with a wash basin. Or «£3,834» if you want an on suite. That's with your own small bathroom.\n\nStudent | 2:55 I see. That's more than I expected.\n\nDarren | 2:58 It does include heating. That's quite a saving because energy costs can be high, especially in winter.\n\nStudent | 3:04 H. Does it include meals as well?\n\nDarren | 3:10 No. All our rooms are self-catering now.\n\nDarren | 3:14 There's a shared kitchen on each corridor where you can cook if you want to, or there are plenty of places to eat out on campus.\n\nStudent | 3:22 Okay. And you said that's the price for the whole year.\n\nDarren | 3:26 Well, you pay annually, but actually it's for 36 weeks. It doesn't include «holidays». You have to vacate the room then.\n\nStudent | 3:35 Oh. Um, I need somewhere to stay in the holidays. I can't afford to go home. The flights are too expensive.\n\nDarren | 3:43 Well, there is another option. Several «families» who either work at the college or have children studying here offer visiting students a room in their homes.\n\nStudent | 3:55 Oh,\n\nDarren | 3:56 we call this arrangement home welcome.\n\nDarren | 3:59 And we've still got a few places left at the moment. You pay £150 per week and that includes breakfast, a packed lunch and dinner as well as heating.\n\nStudent | 4:12 Is there a contract? Do you have to stay for the whole year?\n\nDarren | 4:16 No, it's «flexible».\n\nStudent | 4:18 Um, it sounds really good, but I'm not sure. I really want to be a little more independent.\n\nAnnouncer | 4:29 Before you hear the rest of the conversation, you have some time to look at questions 5 to 10 on page two.\n\n(Khoảng nghỉ từ 4:32 đến 5:06)\n\nAnnouncer | 5:06 Now listen and answer questions 5 to 10.\n\nStudent | 5:13 What about finding somewhere to live off campus?\n\nDarren | 5:16 Yes, you can rent a property in town privately. You might want to rent a room in a shared house. You'd have a room of your own and share the kitchen and bathroom with other students.\n\nStudent | 5:30 What about if I don't want to share?\n\nDarren | 5:32 You can get what we call a «studio».\n\nDarren | 5:35 They're often quite small, but they'll have everything you need,\n\nStudent | 5:39 right? How much would those two options cost?\n\nDarren | 5:42 Well, prices vary depending on which part of town the property is in.\n\nDarren | 5:48 Generally speaking, the cheapest is around £275 a month for each student.\n\nStudent | 5:54 Oh. Uh, that's not too bad.\n\nDarren | 5:57 Yes, but it can also be as high as £490.\n\nDarren | 6:02 And then you'll have to pay all your other bills.\n\nStudent | 6:05 What sort of amount would I be looking at for those?\n\nDarren | 6:08 Well, last year students were paying on average about £43 per month each for gas and electricity. This year it'll probably be somewhere in the region of £48.\n\nStudent | 6:24 That's a lot.\n\nDarren | 6:25 Yes, they've gone up quite a bit. And on top of that, you have to pay for «water» and that'll probably be around £9.\n\nStudent | 6:34 That didn't occur to me. And I guess I'd have to pay for «transportation», too.\n\nDarren | 6:40 That's right. Most of these properties are quite a long way from the college.\n\nStudent | 6:46 It just gets worse and worse.\n\nStudent | 6:49 What's the minimum contract on this type of accommodation?\n\nDarren | 6:53 «6 months». And you have to pay a «deposit», but of course, you can stay there over the holidays.\n\nStudent | 7:00 That's true.\n\nDarren | 7:01 And you'd have to provide «references».\n\nDarren | 7:04 They want two from someone in this country.\n\nStudent | 7:07 I see. That's not a problem.\n\nDarren | 7:10 If you do choose this option, we can't find the property for you. You'd have to go through the estate agent which manages the property for the owner.\n\nStudent | 7:19 Right.\n\nStudent | 7:21 Thanks. Well, I think I'd like to see what's available privately. Could you give me the estate agent details?\n\nAnnouncer | 7:44 That is the end of part one.\n\nAnnouncer | 7:48 You now have one minute to check your answers to part one.","PART 2: Global Museum Audio Guide\n\nAnnouncer | 08:55 Part two.\n\nAnnouncer | 09:00 You will hear an audio guide introducing visitors to a museum.\n\nAnnouncer | 09:05 First, you have some time to look at questions 11 to 15 on page three.\n\n(Khoảng nghỉ từ 09:07 đến 09:40)\n\nAnnouncer | 09:40 Now listen carefully and answer questions 11 to 15.\n\nGuide | 09:48 Welcome to the Global Museum located at the heart of this truly multicultural city which is home to more than 60 different nationalities.\n\nGuide | 09:57 The museum has a number of exciting displays and exhibitions, and this audio guide is designed to help you make the most of your visit.\n\nGuide | 10:04 Altogether, the museum has 18 different galleries, and this season sees the opening of three new exhibitions.\n\nGuide | 10:11 We recommend that you begin your tour by visiting this season's highlights.\n\nGuide | 10:19 The Heritage Clothes exhibition is located in gallery 5 of the museum.\n\nGuide | 10:24 «People who live in the area» have spent two years preparing this exhibition, which brings together some of the fascinating garments traditionally worn in their own communities.\n\nGuide | 10:35 They researched the history of their community's clothing traditions and the customs and rituals associated with them.\n\nGuide | 10:41 Altogether, 16 countries are represented from Ghana to Korea, from Turkey to Nepal.\n\nGuide | 10:49 The photographs that accompany each display case were taken by some of the city college students who are studying design and show the clothes being modeled by «the real people who wear them in the course of their everyday lives.»\n\nGuide | 11:03 Another highlight this season is the exhibition called Toys from the Past, which can be found in Gallery 9.\n\nGuide | 11:11 This exhibition, which will appeal to people of all ages, is on tour throughout the country and will be here for «10 weeks only».\n\nGuide | 11:19 The exhibits include dolls made over a hundred years ago with beautiful porcelain faces and in some cases real hair.\n\nGuide | 11:27 The collection covers the favorite toys such as wooden train sets from many different generations and provides plenty of interest for children and adults.\n\nGuide | 11:37 The gigantic «board games» which are laid out on the gallery floor are one of the most popular activities in the exhibition and« should not be missed.»\n\nGuide | 11:47 This exhibition concludes with a special display of miniature toys.\n\nGuide | 11:50 These small objects are «on loan» from countries all over the world and in some cases measure no more than a few cm.\n\nGuide | 12:01 There's a tiny car made from matchsticks, a toy airplane complete with pilot and passengers made out of seashells, and some exquisite little buildings no higher than 4 cm.\n\nAnnouncer | 12:15 Before you hear the rest of the talk, you have some time to look at questions 16 to 20 on pages 3 and 4.\n\n(Khoảng nghỉ từ 12:20 đến 12:53)\n\nAnnouncer | 12:53 Now listen and answer questions 16 to 20.\n\nGuide | 13:00 The final gallery highlight of the season is the Biscuit Gallery at number 15.\n\nGuide | 13:06 Many years ago, this city was famous for its biscuits, although today the factory no longer exists.\n\nGuide | 13:13 Did you know, for example, that before biscuits were packed in paper or cardboard boxes, biscuit tins were fashion items?\n\nGuide | 13:20 The factory made «tins, round, square, triangular, hexagonal», for a whole range of different occasions to celebrate national events, festivals, famous faces, and so on.\n\nGuide | 13:35 One fascinating display deals with people's favorite biscuits.\n\nGuide | 13:37 There are sweet biscuits and savory ones. Biscuits filled with jam and biscuits filled with currants.\n\nGuide | 13:44 Biscuits with pink, yellow, and white sugar icing or colored sugar flowers.\n\nGuide | 13:52 When the factory finally closed, it announced that people's favorite biscuit was not, as you might expect, a chocolate biscuit, or one filled with jam and cream, but «a plain savory one» which was eaten with cheese.\n\nGuide | 14:06 When you get to the end of the exhibition, there's an entertaining, hands-on activity to« fill your own biscuit tin».\n\nGuide | 14:12 All the biscuits ever produced by the company are piled up on a table along with various tins.\n\nGuide | 14:20 The biscuits are made out of thin pieces of wood, but the weight, colors, and shapes replicate the original biscuits.\n\nGuide | 14:29 Your job is to fill a tin with biscuits so that when the lid is taken off, they sit there as neatly as they did when the job was done by machine.\n\nGuide | 14:35 It's not as easy as it looks.\n\nGuide | 14:40 If you would like to buy a memento of your visit, there is a museum gift shop selling postcards, souvenirs, and handmade pottery next to the information desk on «the ground floor».\n\nGuide | 14:51 And finally, if you don't want to carry your «coats and bags» around with you during your visit, please make use of the free lockers provided by the museum.\n\nGuide | 15:00 Enjoy your visit.\n\nAnnouncer | 15:20 That is the end of part two.\n\nAnnouncer | 15:24 You now have 30 seconds to check your answers to part two.","PART 3: Anthropology Assignment on Tapa Cloth\n\nAnnouncer | 16:00 Part three.\n\nAnnouncer | 16:06 You will hear a discussion between a student called Helen and her tutor about an assignment that Helen is working on.\n\nAnnouncer | 16:14 First, you have some time to look at questions 21 to 24 on page 5.\n\n(Khoảng nghỉ từ 16:16 đến 16:50)\n\nAnnouncer | 16:50 Now listen carefully and answer questions 21 to 24.\n\nTutor | 16:58 Come in Helen. How can I help you?\n\nHelen | 17:00 Well, I'm doing research for the anthropology assignment and I was hoping to check a few details.\n\nTutor | 17:07 Sure. You chose the topic of Pacific Island Tupper Cloth, didn't you? What have you found out so far?\n\nHelen | 17:14 Well, I was going to introduce my assignment by saying that the Tupperloth is a fabric made from bark, just the outer layer of the trees.\n\nHelen | 17:24 It's particularly common in the Pacific Islands, but not exclusive to them. In fact, many other peoples around the world have made high quality cloth from bark.\n\nHelen | 17:33 But what sets Pacific Tapper apart is« the incredible variety of roles» it's played in this region.\n\nTutor | 17:41 Yes, nice introduction, though I think you could be more specific regarding dates. Okay, so what about the raw materials used?\n\nHelen | 17:51 Well, taper cloth is made from several species of tree in the Pacific.\n\nHelen | 17:54 The paper mulberry tree is most common, but it doesn't thrive in all conditions. In fact, «it wasn't originally found in the islands», but was carried in their canoes by the first migrants.\n\nHelen | 18:07 Tapa is also made from the bread fruit tree, which is convenient because its fruit is a staple food. The paper mulberry tree is only grown for tapa making, though.\n\nTutor | 18:22 Yes, that's good. Now, what about the Mari people here in New Zealand?\n\nHelen | 18:28 But the Mai don't make taper now.\n\nTutor | 18:30 That's right. and you need to account for it.\n\nTutor | 18:32 We know that when Mari migrated here from the other Pacific islands, they were prepared to make taper because they brought the paper mulberry tree with them.\n\nTutor | 18:41 The thing was, after they'd been in New Zealand a bit, they found the« flax plant», which is «superior» to taper because it makes a «stronger fabric.»\n\nTutor | 18:52 By the time Europeans arrived in the 18th century, Mari were making all their fabric from flax and had been for some time.\n\nHelen | 18:59 Okay. So with the production process itself, first the inner bark is beaten with wooden hammers to soften the fibers.\n\nHelen | 19:08 Then the different pieces are glued together using« an adhesive paste »made from the arrowroot tuber.\n\nHelen | 19:17 This is the only way to fabricate large pieces of cloth because bark strands are too fine to be woven together and stitching isn't strong enough.\n\nAnnouncer | 19:29 Before you hear the rest of the discussion, you have some time to look at questions 25 to 30 on page six.\n\n(Khoảng nghỉ từ 19:33 đến 20:07)\n\nAnnouncer | 20:07 Now listen and answer questions 25 to 30.\n\nTutor | 20:13 So now you need details about different countries. Where would you start?\n\nHelen | 20:18 I think Samo is the obvious place. It's famous for its very fine cloth called siapo which is handpainted with representations of the ancestors.\n\nHelen | 20:29 Still today at the most profound «events in life such as births, funerals, weddings», and the investiture of chiefs, sowans wear siapo robes to add significance and meaning to the ceremony.\n\nTutor | 20:44 Okay, then I could talk about Tonga.\n\nTutor | 20:47 It seems to me that the great innovation in Tonga has been developing a simple coarse cloth which is quick and easy to make.\n\nTutor | 20:55 This is suitable for all sorts of «everyday functions» around the house like bed covers, mosquito nets, and curtains.\n\nHelen | 21:04 Good point. Now, what about Cook Islands, Tupper?\n\nHelen | 21:09 Well, the soil there is poor quality, so the bread fruit tree is often used.\n\nHelen | 21:15 One type of thick cloth called ticoru was wrapped around the poles and used to mark the entrances to« places of worship». So it was highly regarded in local culture.\n\nTutor | 21:26 You might mention Fiji as well, which is interesting because tapa was actually «used as a currency» there.\n\nTutor | 21:34 Fijians used to sail between the islands and exchange taper for other commodities like canoes or pigs.\n\nHelen | 21:39 I know that in Tahiti the taper cloth is different because the patterns are in color which is considered more valuable than the usual brown patterns.\n\nTutor | 21:49 You're right about the Tahesians using colored pigments but they aren't more valuable. The colors are only a decoration.\n\nTutor | 21:56 People enjoy wearing bright robes, especially for «dancing and competitive games »and do it just for fun.\n\nHelen | 22:04 Oh, I'll make a note of that. Well, the last place I was going to mention was Tikopia.\n\nHelen | 22:10 Even today, it's common place to see people wearing clothes made of taper cloth.\n\nHelen | 22:15 In many of the other islands, the taper only comes out on special occasions. But here, you see people «working in the gardens» wearing tappa\n\nTutor | 22:25 Sounds promising, Helen. I'll look forward to reading your assignment.\n\nAnnouncer | 22:42 That is the end of part three.\n\nAnnouncer | 22:45 You now have 30 seconds to check your answers to part three."],"listening-w1-classwork":["Midbury Drama Club\n\nRobert | 02:14 Hello, Robert Gladwell speaking.\n\nChloe | 02:20 Oh, hi. My name's Chloe Martin. I was given your name and phone number by Ben Winters. I work with him and he said you're a member of Midbury Drama Club.\n\nRobert | 02:32 Yes, I am.\n\nChloe | 02:34 Well, I've just moved to the area and I'm keen to join a drama club.\n\nRobert | 02:38 Great. Yes, I can give you some information. We're one of the oldest drama clubs in the area. As the club started in 1957, we now have about 60 members. Our youngest member is 10 and our oldest member is 78.\n\nChloe | 02:54 Oh, I think I saw a picture in the newspaper the other day of some of your members being presented with a prize.\n\nRobert | 03:01 Yes. «The youth»«(Q1)» section did very well in a competition and won £100, which will help with their next production. Anyway, uh, tell me a bit more about yourself.\n\nChloe | 03:15 Well, I've done a bit of acting. I was in a couple of musicals when I was at university and a historical play more recently.\n\nRobert | 03:23 H, we mainly do «comedy»«(Q2)» plays. We get good audiences for that kind of thing. We haven't attempted a musical yet, but we might do one soon.\n\nChloe | 03:33 Oh. Um, when do you usually meet?\n\nRobert | 03:38 On Tuesdays.\n\nChloe | 03:40 Well, presumably I'll need to do an audition.\n\nRobert | 03:43 Yes, there were a few auditions last Tuesday and we'll be doing more at our next meeting which is in two weeks' time. That's on Tuesday the «12 March»«(Q3)». There'll be another opportunity 2 weeks after that which will be on the 26th of March.\n\nChloe | 04:00 Oh, well, I can come to your next meeting and if I don't get an acting part in a play, I'd be happy to help with something else. I've designed publicity before.\n\nRobert | 04:10 Great. We're very short of people who can do that. So, that would be really good. There are a lot of people who like making scenery, so we get plenty of help with that, but we haven't got enough people to do the «lights»«(Q4)» at the moment. So, if you think you can do that, or you have any friends who would like to, uh, do bring them along. We can show you what to do if you haven't got any experience.\n\nChloe | 04:36 I'll have to think about it. So, do you meet in the theater?\n\nRobert | 04:40 We do our performances in the Mana Theater, but we only hire that for the nights of the actual performances. We meet to rehearse every Tuesday evening in the «community hall»«(Q5)». We rented a room there.\n\nChloe | 04:54 Oh, I'm not sure where that is. I'll be coming by car because I don't live in the town center.\n\nRobert | 05:00 It's in Ash Burton Road. As you're coming towards the center down Regent Street, you need to turn left at the crossroads.\n\nChloe | 05:08 Oh, I know. There's a big car park down there just before you get to a hotel. It's on the other side of the road from the «sports center»«(Q6)».\n\nRobert | 05:18 That's it. That's the closest place to leave your car. And you don't have to pay in the evening to park there. We meet at 7:30 and we usually finish by 9:30 or 10:00.\n\nNarrator | 05:31 Before you hear the rest of the conversation, you have some time to look at questions 7 to 10.\n\nNarrator | 06:21 Now listen and answer questions 7 to 10.\n\nRobert | 06:28 I haven't mentioned that we have to make a charge. Everyone pays a subscription of «£180»«(Q7)» to be a member for a year. You can pay for the whole year at once or you can pay £15 every month. It works out the same. There are reductions for retired people and under 18s, but I don't think you come into either category.\n\nChloe | 06:51 No, I'm 26.\n\nRobert | 06:53 Oh, that fee covers all the costs like photocopying of scripts and producing the posters, but it excludes the «costumes»«(Q8)» for the performances. We ask people to pay for the hire of those themselves. It does mean they look after them properly as they know they won't get their deposit back otherwise.\n\nChloe | 07:16 Can I come along to the next meeting then?\n\nRobert | 07:18 Of course. We'd love to see you. And if you want to know more about how we run the auditions or the next play we're doing, why don't you give our secretary a ring? She'll be really pleased to help you.\n\nChloe | 07:33 Oh, what's her name?\n\nRobert | 07:33 It's Sarah Sordicott. That's «S-A-W-D-I-C-O double T»«(Q9)».\n\nChloe | 07:47 Got that. And her phone number?\n\nRobert | 07:49 I've only got a mobile number for her. Um, just a minute. Uh, let me find it. Ah, yes. It's um «07955240063»«(Q10)».\n\nChloe | 08:07 Great. Thanks for your help.","Forward Thinking Charity\n\nNarrator | 09:30 Part two. You will hear a radio program in which a presenter called Jasmine tells her colleague Fergus about a charity. First, you have some time to look at questions 11 to 15.\n\nNarrator | 10:54 Now listen carefully and answer questions 11 to 15.\n\nFergus | 11:02 And now here's Jasmine who's come to tell us about this week's charity. Hi Fergus.\n\nJasmine | 11:08 This week I'm going to talk about forward thinking and their plans for the Kovville Center. So in recent years, people have realized how useful the arts can be within healthcare. «The idea behind forward thinking is to use the arts to promote well-being»«(Q11)».\n\nJasmine | 11:27 The charity develops projects for people with special needs and health problems and also delivers training to healthcare professionals in using the arts as well as supplying them with information and advice. Forward thinking doesn't just run art and craft classes to distract people who are ill or recovering from illness, but arranges longer-term projects and courses. As it's been shown that the arts can bring all sorts of positive changes in patients, including benefits such as shortening the length of stay in hospital and «reducing the amounts of medicine they need»«(Q12)».\n\nFergus | 12:06 I see.\n\nJasmine | 12:08 Forward Thinking has experience of working with a broad range of people from young adults with learning difficulties to older people in homes or daycare centers and people with physical disabilities. The organization's been around since 1986 and it gradually expanded during the 1990s. Then in the new millennium, it was decided to find a memorable name.« So it's been operating as forward thinking for several years—uh in fact since 2005»«(Q13)». It's quite a locally based charity mainly for people in the southern part of this region which includes« all rural and urban communities outside the city of Clifton which has its own organization»«(Q14)». There are of course some similar charities in other parts of the country in London and so on.\n\nFergus | 12:58 H and what's the present fundraising in aid of?\n\nJasmine | 13:02 Yeah. Well, the charity needs funding in order to buy the Coleville Center. This is a former village school which was built in 1868. It was modernized and refurbished by the present owners last year. So, «it's ideal for art classes and for small social events, performances, seminars, and so on»«(Q15)». Forward thinking is fundraising to purchase the building so they can use it to continue running classes and so on for the general public and eventually also for some of the people they help.\n\nNarrator | 13:37 Before you hear the rest of the talk, you have some time to look at questions 16 to 20.\n\nNarrator | 14:26 Now listen and answer questions 16 to 20.\n\nFergus | 14:33 Right. So can you give us a few ideas about what classes people might do there? Is it all art classes?\n\nJasmine | 14:40 Um well there are some very good art classes but there are lots of other things going on as well. So for example there's learning salsa with Nina Bellina's team. They say that salsa is an easy dance to learn. It's also an excellent form of exercise according to Nina. «And that class is for both men and women of course»«(Q16)». It's ideal for beginners and what they call refreshers. That's £100 for 10 sessions.\n\nJasmine | 15:15 Then another class is called Smooth Movers. It's with Kevin Bennett and «it's for you if you don't have the same energy levels as you used to when you were a teenager»«(Q17)». It's a gentle exercise class geared to the needs of whoever is in the group in a particular session. And Kevin is qualified to teach classes to people getting over injuries and so on and balance training. That's £60 for 10 sessions.\n\nJasmine | 15:42 Then there's a day called Art of the Forest with Jamie Graham where you discover Upper Wood, a short walk from the Cville Center, and learn how to design in 3D with natural materials. It's an unusual and exciting way to be creative. Jamie is an artist with a background also as a country park ranger. «For this day, youngsters must be accompanied by a parent or guardian»«(Q18)». And the costs are adults £40, under 14s, £10, but it's best value at £80 for a family of four.\n\nJasmine | 16:21 The next one is the money maze, and this is a series of talks by Peter O'Reilly, an independent financial adviser. He gives advice on family finances. «Things like everything parents need to know about managing the costs of bringing up children»«(Q19)», sending them to university, and actually also about care for elderly relatives. It's £10 per talk, which will all go to support forward thinking.\n\nJasmine | 16:51 And as a final example of what's on offer, there's “Make A Play”. «That's for 8 to 14s»«(Q20)». And this activity is such a hit that it usually sells out within days of being announced. Basically, what you do is write, rehearse, and perform a play in just 2 days. And it doesn't require any previous experience. I gather there's lots of fun and silliness along the way. And the best bit perhaps is that there's a performance for family and friends at the end. It's just £50 for 2 days.\n\nFergus | 17:24 Pretty good range of activities I think and all raising money for a good cause.\n\nJasmine | 17:31 Yes. And the all important contact details are cowville@forwardthinking.org.uk or write to me."],"listening-w2-classwork":["Transcript\n\nJames | 02:12 Hello, McFadden's Travel. James speaking. How may I help you?\n\nJonathon | 02:17 Hi there. My name's Jonathon Presley, principal of Sainsbury Secondary School. I am calling to ask about your early bird tour offer. I saw it advertised in the Evening Herald yesterday.\n\nJames | 02:30 Certainly, Mr. Presley. What would you like to know?\n\nJonathon | 02:33 Oh, please. Jonathon will be fine.\n\nJames | 02:36 Of course, Jonathon. How can I help you?\n\nJonathon | 02:39 Well, the first thing I'd like to know is how long is your offer valid for? My third-year students are planning a holiday in early April. Will they qualify for the discount?\n\nJames | 02:50 The good news is our special offer runs until the end of «May»«(Q1)».\n\nJonathon | 02:55 Oh dear. Oh dear. March. That's terrible. We've just missed out.\n\nJames | 03:00 On the contrary, Jonathon, it's May, not March. You will qualify for the discount.\n\nJonathon | 03:05 Oh, fantastic.\n\nJames | 03:08 And I'm only just getting started. The best news is yet to come.\n\nJonathon | 03:12 What do you mean?\n\nJames | 03:14 Well, tell me now, how many students are you planning to take on this tour?\n\nJonathon | 03:19 I expect there will be about 45 students and three teachers accompanying them. Why are there any further discounts?\n\nJames | 03:27 There are indeed. We do a 25% discount on groups of up to 40 people. For you, we can offer an even better rate. A 50% discount.\n\nJonathon | 03:38 Wow. Is that on top of the 15% early bird discount?\n\nJames | 03:42 It most certainly is. Which makes your total tour discount um 50 + 15 «65 percent»«(Q2)».\n\nJonathon | 03:52 Surely there's a catch. This is too good to be true.\n\nJames | 03:55 Well, there is a condition that you must choose your destination from a list we have selected. You can't book a tour to just anywhere in the world with this discount rate.\n\nJonathon | 04:05 I see. And would Madrid be on that list by any chance?\n\nJames | 04:09 I'm sorry to disappoint you, but we do not offer this rate on tours to Madrid. However, we have an excellent all-inclusive 7-day Barcelona tour which is available. How does that sound?\n\nJonathon | 04:21 Sounds interesting. What is the total cost per student?\n\nJames | 04:26 Let's see. It works out at £679 per person with the discount. The normal price is «1,940 pounds »«(Q3)». So, you are saving £1,261 per person.\n\nJonathon | 04:42 Hold on a moment. Let me get a pen to write some of this down. It's getting complicated. Okay. How much will it cost per student?\n\nJames | 04:52 £679.\n\nJonathon | 04:54 And how much of a saving is that?\n\nJames | 04:56 £1,261.\n\nJonathon | 05:00 Barcelona sounds very good indeed. Tell me, what do you mean by all-inclusive? What does £679 get us?\n\nNarrator | 05:11 Before you hear the rest of the conversation, you have some time to look at questions 4 to 10.\n\n(6:06)Now listen and answer questions 4 to 10.\n\nJames | 06:12 Well, that price covers flights, three-star hotel accommodation, and extras.\n\nJonathon | 06:18 James, I must say I'm very glad I called you this morning. This is a fantastic deal. [clears throat] It covers «flights»«(Q4)», «accommodation»«(Q5)», and what else?\n\nJames | 06:27 Plus airport «taxis»«(Q6)», «breakfast»«(Q7)» every morning, a city tour, and theater tickets.\n\nJonathon | 06:34 Great. And what about the teachers?\n\nJames | 06:37 The teachers can travel free of charge with the students.\n\nJonathon | 06:40 Well, I might just go on this tour myself. I've always fancied a trip to Barcelona, but uh for the children's sake, of course.\n\nJames | 06:49 Of course. Now, let's get to work on the booking. Exactly when were you planning to leave?\n\nJonathon | 06:57 The 7th of April, if possible.\n\nJames | 07:00 Yes, that's available. And can you confirm the exact number of students, please?\n\nJonathon | 07:06 It's either 44 or 45. Uh let me see. Yes, 45. Exactly 45 students. No, sorry. Uh, in fact, that's 46. I forgot about Jenny McCarthy. She sent her application in late, so it's not in the same pile as the rest.\n\nJames | 07:26 So, that's the 7th of April and 46 students. Correct.\n\nJonathon | 07:30 Yes. Perfect. And three teachers. Is there a morning flight?\n\nJames | 07:35 Yes. Your flight is at «7:00 am»«(Q8)». on Monday, the 7th of April. Arrive at the airport 2 hours before departure. The flight will take about 2 and 1/2 hours, and you'll land at 10:30 a.m. local time. How does that sound?\n\nJonathon | 07:51 Sounds great. Can I give you my email address to confirm the rest of the details?\n\nJames | 07:57 Of course.\n\nJonathon | 07:58 It's Jonathon.presley@sainsbury.com. That's «j o n a t h o n . p r e s l e y @ s a i n s b u r y .com»«(Q9)» and we'll pay by credit card if possible.\n\nJames | 08:24 That'll be perfect. What's your card number?\n\nJonathon | 08:28 It's «6676665497431251»«(Q10)». Expiry date 01 Jan 2015 and the name on the credit card... That's my own Jonathon [clears throat] Presley.\n\nJames | 08:46 So £679 times 46 students. Um, I'm going to charge £31,234 to your credit card. That's the total cost.\n\nJonathon | 09:00 Sounds fine.\n\nJames | 09:02 Great. Well, I think that's all we need for now, Jonathon. It's been a pleasure doing business with you. If you have any questions, please don't hesitate to give me a call. We'll be in touch next week to confirm the booking details.\n\nJonathon | 09:16 Okay. And thank you very much for your help, James. Bye for now.\n\nJames | 09:19 Bye-bye, Jonathon. Speak soon.\n\nNarrator | 09:49 That is the end of part one. You now have one minute to check your answers to part one.","PART 1: Island Hotel Inquiry\n\nAnnouncer | 0:01 This is the IELTS listening test.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:05 You will hear a number of different recordings and you will have to answer questions on what you hear.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:13 There will be time for you to read the instructions and questions and you will have a chance to check your work.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:21 All the recordings will be played once only. The test is in four parts.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:29 At the end of the test, you will be given 10 minutes to transfer your answers to the answer sheet.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:37 Now, turn to part one. Part one.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:54 You will hear a man phoning to inquire about hotel information.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:59 First, you have some time to look at questions 1 to four.\n\n(Khoảng nghỉ từ 1:03 đến 1:44)\n\nAnnouncer | 1:44 Now we shall begin. You should answer the questions as you listen because you will not hear the recording a second time.\n\nAnnouncer | 1:54 Listen carefully and answer questions 1 to four.\n\nReceptionist | 2:00 Good afternoon. You're through to reception at the Island Hotel in Cree. How may I help you today?\n\nCustomer | 2:06 Yes. Hello there. I'm hoping to book a double room for my wife and myself for about 2 weeks from the «25th of April» of this year. Firstly, could you tell me whether it's particularly hot during this time?\n\nReceptionist | 2:21 Yes, of course, sir. During late April and early May, the daytime temperature shouldn't exceed 19° C, but the weather has been rather «erratic» and difficult to predict in recent years, so I am unable to say for certain.\n\nCustomer | 2:36 Okay, that sounds good. My wife doesn't like going outside when it's very hot. I haven't booked flights yet, but I must say that I'm unfamiliar with Creed and its transport system. Does the hotel provide an airport shuttle service?\n\nReceptionist | 2:50 Yes, sir. We provide a complimentary airport pickup service for all our guests. It takes about« 40 minutes» to get here from the airport, but it's at least 60 minutes at rush hours, and you will be provided with a fully conditioned shuttle bus.\n\nCustomer | 3:08 Okay, excellent. In that case, do you have any rooms available for the dates I gave you?\n\nReceptionist | 3:13 I shall have a look at the system now for you, sir. Bear with me just a moment.\n\nReceptionist | 3:18 Yes, sir. I can see now that we have several rooms available. Would you prefer a garden view or a sea view?\n\nCustomer | 3:26 Well, ideally I would like a sea view room with a balcony, but of course that depends on the difference in price.\n\nReceptionist | 3:33 Not to worry, sir. All of our standard double rooms have «ensuite» facilities and a «balcony». If you would like one of our sea view rooms, there is a premium of €60 per night.\n\nCustomer | 3:46 Okay. So, could you tell me the total nightly rate for a standard double room with a C view?\n\nReceptionist | 3:52 Yes, of course, sir. For the spring months, our rate is €216 per night. For 14 nights altogether, this will come to €3,024.\n\nCustomer | 4:04 Perfect. I also read on your website that the hotel has gym and spa facilities. Are there any other facilities on offer?\n\nReceptionist | 4:11 Yes, we have a large outdoor infinity pool overlooking the ocean with luxury sunbeds and a poolside bar. We also have three full-size tennis courts where we run a popular doubles tournament with the winner receiving two all-inclusive spa day vouchers.\n\nCustomer | 4:32 Goodness, I shall brush up on my tennis skills.\n\nAnnouncer | 4:38 Before you hear the rest of the conversation, you have some time to look at questions 5 to 10.\n\n(Khoảng nghỉ từ 4:42 đến 5:05)\n\nAnnouncer | 5:05 Now listen and answer questions 5 to 10.\n\nCustomer | 5:11 Are there any other activities organized by the hotel that we can partake in? It's just that it's our wedding anniversary on the 30th of June, and I would like to provide my wife with a perfect romantic getaway.\n\nReceptionist | 5:25 I can assure you, sir, that your wife won't be disappointed. Ours is a five-star resort which is renowned for its luxury and beauty.\n\nReceptionist | 5:32 In terms of activities, the hotel provides thrice weekly entertainment. On Tuesdays, guests will take a mini bus and partake in learning to cook succulent «fish dishes »with our Michelin starred chef Enrique.\n\nReceptionist | 5:51 The class will take place in a beautiful valley deep in the Cretton Hills where guests will be treated to an intimate «piano» performance by our in-house concert pianist Pedro.\n\nReceptionist | 6:02 On Wednesdays, a select number of guests will be fortunate enough to explore the mountains by helicopter before being transported to a tropical cretan «garden» by shuttle bus.\n\nReceptionist | 6:19 Finally, on Thursdays, after a «fancy dinner», we provide a spectacular «fireworks» display which guests can view from the comfort of a «cable car».\n\nCustomer | 6:28 Oh, wow. That all sounds absolutely wonderful. I shall book the room now and then I need to look at flights so as not to become extortionate. Would you like to take my details now or later?\n\nAnnouncer | 6:59 That is the end of part one.\n\nAnnouncer | 7:03 You now have one minute to check your answers to part one."],"listening-w4-classwork":["PART 1: Queenstown Trip Planning\n\nAnnouncer | 00:01 This is the IELTS listening test. You will hear a number of different recordings and you will have to answer questions on what you hear.\n\nAnnouncer | 00:13 There will be time for you to read the instructions and questions and you will have a chance to check your work.\n\nAnnouncer | 00:21 All the recordings will be played once only. The test is in four parts.\n\nAnnouncer | 00:29 At the end of the test, you will be given 10 minutes to transfer your answers to the answer sheet. Now, turn to part one.\n\nAnnouncer | 00:51 Part one. You will hear two students, Justinta and Lewis, discussing a holiday they are planning in Queenstown, a tourist center in New Zealand popular with young people.\n\nAnnouncer | 01:02 First, you have some time to look at questions 1 to six.\n\nAnnouncer | 02:01 Now we shall begin. You should answer the questions as you listen because you will not hear the recording a second time. Listen carefully and answer questions 1 to six.\n\nJustinta | 02:23 Hi Louis, it's Justinta here.\n\nLouis | 02:25 Oh, hi Justinta. I was just going to call you. I was thinking we ought to do something about accommodation for our trip to Queenstown.\n\nJustinta | 02:33 Yeah, actually that's just why I rang you. I've been looking on the internet. There was one place that looked okay called Traveler's Lodge. But when I checked availability for January, when we're planning to go, I found it was fully booked,\n\nLouis | 02:49 right? Well, we better do something now, I suppose.\n\nJustinta | 02:54 I've actually got a list up here on the computer. There's one place called Bingley's that looks possible. It's «$19.75» a night. That's US dollars. They quote all the prices in US dollars. So that's about 26 or 27 New Zealand dollars.\n\nLouis | 03:12 That's okay. That'll be in a dormitory, is it?\n\nJustinta | 03:15 Yeah, they say 8 bed dorms. And the hostel's right in the town center and they've got a cafe. They have «theme» nights every weekend, whatever that means.\n\nLouis | 03:25 Oh, you know, like certain sorts of food and music and people might wear special clothes like that Egyptian evening we went to last year.\n\nJustinta | 03:34 Oh, okay. What else? They've got a sun deck area and then all the usual things, internet access and so on.\n\nLouis | 03:43 Sounds good. Was there anywhere else?\n\nJustinta | 03:46 Yeah, a couple more places. There's one called Chalet Lodge, which is just $18. That's for a bed in a 12 bed dorm. They do single and family rooms as well. It looks as if it's a bit out of town. says it's got an alpine setting. A «quiet» alpine setting. What do you think?\n\nLouis | 04:09 Not sure.\n\nJustinta | 04:11 Oh, but actually it's not far out at all. It says 10 minutes walk from town, so\n\nLouis | 04:19 Oh, and it says it's« children »friendly. I'm not so sure about that. What about the third place?\n\nJustinta | 04:27 Uh, that's called Globe Trotters. Let's see. They do private rooms or five bed dorms for $18.50. It's in the center just by the lake. And that includes «breakfast».\n\nLouis | 04:42 Didn't the other two?\n\nJustinta | 04:43 I don't think so. They didn't mention it, so probably not. Oh, and it says something about a free «skydive». Wow.\n\nLouis | 04:53 Don't know if I'm all that keen on jumping out of airplanes. Oh, actually what it says is you can win a chance to do a skydive. They give one away every day to one of the guests.\n\nJustinta | 05:06 Well, if I win it, you can do it. Anyway, do they have room?\n\nLouis | 05:10 Yeah, I'll check the availability. Shall I go ahead and book there then?\n\nJustinta | 05:14 Fine.\n\nAnnouncer | 05:18 You now have some time to look at questions 7 to 10.\n\nAnnouncer | 05:49 Now listen and answer questions 7 to 10.\n\nJustinta | 05:56 I was looking at what there is to do too. There are lots of sites offering deals for «adventure »sports. I suppose we have to do a bungee jump.\n\nLouis | 06:05 Why?\n\nJustinta | 06:06 Well, it's Queenstown where they more or less started it as a sport.\n\nLouis | 06:10 You can if you really want to jump off the side of a bridge with an elastic rope tied around your ankles. I'll watch.\n\nJustinta | 06:17 Okay. So, what do you want to do?\n\nLouis | 06:20 As far as adventure sports go, I was talking to someone who went «white-water »rafting there. He said it was really awesome. They drive you up the shot over the river and then come down on a rubber raft through the white-water rapids where the river is really narrow and fast and end up going through a tunnel nearly 200 m long. I think it's quite expensive though.\n\nJustinta | 06:43 Oh, I'm on for that if you are\n\nLouis | 06:46 cool.\n\nJustinta | 06:47 The other thing you can do is the jetboat «ride». That sounded just a lot of noise though. It's basically just whizzing around on the river on a very fast boat, isn't it? My friend did that as well. He said it was a bit touristy, but worth it. I'll give it a go. You go right up the river canyon. He said the drivers were really skillful, but I don't mind going on my own.\n\nLouis | 07:11 But there's lots to do as well as the whole commercial adventure, but we ought to do some «trekking». The scenery around there is amazing. I don't want to miss that. The place to start Glenori, apparently, is about a 40 minutes drive. That's where lots of the wilderness trails begin.\n\nJustinta | 07:27 Okay, I'll pack my walking boots. I better start getting training. I haven't done anything except sit at my desk for months now. Is there anything else we need to decide?\n\nAnnouncer | 07:55 That is the end of part one. You now have one minute to check your answers to part one.","PART 2: Cycling Courses in London\n\nAnnouncer | 09:07 part two.\n\nAnnouncer | 09:11 You will hear a local radio program about cycling courses in London.\n\nAnnouncer | 09:16 First, you have some time to look at questions 11 to 14.\n\nAnnouncer | 09:51 Now listen carefully and answer questions 11 to 14.\n\nRadio Host | 09:59 There's been a great deal of interest lately in encouraging people to use bicycles instead of cars as a means of transport.\n\nRadio Host | 10:05 But not everyone is confident about riding a bike at the best of times, let alone in the middle of a city like London.\n\nRadio Host | 10:12 Jack Hayes is a professional trainer who works for a London-based company, City Cyclist, which provides cycle training for the public.\n\nRadio Host | 10:22 What exactly does a city cyclist do, Jack?\n\nJack Hayes | 10:26 Well, our basic purpose is to promote cycling as a sustainable form of transport.\n\nJack Hayes | 10:32 We believe the best way to promote cycling is to teach people to use their bikes safely and with confidence.\n\nJack Hayes | 10:39 In European countries, people all learned from their parents and they also learned in school.\n\nJack Hayes | 10:44 And when I tell them I teach people to ride bikes, they laugh. They think it's crazy.\n\nJack Hayes | 10:49 But here in London, it's completely different.\n\nJack Hayes | 10:52 You're approaching the point where« a whole generation of people have grown up not being allowed by their parents to cycle» because it was considered to be getting too dangerous and so in turn they can't teach their children.\n\nJack Hayes | 11:07 We believe in realistic training.\n\nJack Hayes | 11:10 So if someone wants to use a bike regularly, say to get to work or school, we aim to train them by «teaching them to ride on the actual roads they'll use» so they can develop the basic skills they need and build up their confidence that way.\n\nJack Hayes | 11:25 At City Cyclist, we believe cycling's for everyone, no matter what age or level of ability or mobility.\n\nJack Hayes | 11:30 We do complete beginners and also advanced courses.\n\nJack Hayes | 11:36 That's for urban cyclists who want to deal with things like riding in streets with «complicated intersections» and things like that.\n\nJack Hayes | 11:43 We don't promote the use of personal protective equipment for cyclists and we endorse the policy of the European Cyclists Federation that parents should be allowed to make an informed choice as to whether or not their child wears a helmet.\n\nJack Hayes | 11:59 We believe the key to safe cycling is assertiveness, taking your place on the road.\n\nJack Hayes | 12:04 This has to be instilled right from the beginning. «Assertive road positioning and behavior» is the key to safe cycling in congested urban environments.\n\nJack Hayes | 12:16 Some people are surprised that we don't promote the segregation of cyclists from motorized traffic, but we don't think that's practical in all urban environments.\n\nJack Hayes | 12:24 Instead, we teach people to use as much road space as they need to travel safely and effectively.\n\nAnnouncer | 12:35 You now have some time to look at questions 15 to me.\n\nAnnouncer | 13:07 Now listen and answer questions 15 to 20.\n\nJack Hayes | 13:14 Now as well as courses for individuals, City Cyclist provides a number of services for organizations.\n\nJack Hayes | 13:21 For example, «we can deliver fun safe cycle training activities at schools», arranging courses so that the disruption of curriculum time is kept to a minimum.\n\nJack Hayes | 13:31 As well as this, in order to promote safe cycling, «we have provided training courses for employees and staff of local councils.»\n\nJack Hayes | 13:39 And «we are also increasingly looking at developing training courses in companies »in order to help employers work towards green transport plans by helping to increase the number of staff cycling to work.\n\nJack Hayes | 13:50 Right? So that's a brief summary of what we do.\n\nJack Hayes | 13:53 If any listeners would like to find out more about the organization, you can have a look at our website. That's city cyclist ci.co.uk.\n\nJack Hayes | 14:08 And in order to book lessons, «you can either phone us on 027562428 or do it online.»\n\nJack Hayes | 14:16 There's an application form on our website and you can just download that and send it in.\n\nJack Hayes | 14:23 We charge «£27.50 per hour for one-to-one lessons» plus £6 for each extra person.\n\nJack Hayes | 14:27 So you're looking at just £39.50 for a family of three, say, if you've never been on a bike in your life before, we reckon we can get you riding in 1 hour.\n\nJack Hayes | 14:41 And for most people, «a course of road training usually takes 3 hours.»\n\nJack Hayes | 14:46 But whether you're a parent or a child, an individual or an institution, we'll be happy to discuss your special needs and make a program just for you.\n\nAnnouncer | 15:10 That is the end of part two.\n\nAnnouncer | 15:14 You now have 30 seconds to check your answers to part two.","PART 3: University Tutorial on City Traffic\n\nAnnouncer | 15:50 Part three.\n\nAnnouncer | 15:56 You will hear a discussion between three people in a university tutorial.\n\nAnnouncer | 16:01 In the first part of the discussion, they're talking about city traffic and the motor car.\n\nAnnouncer | 16:07 First look at questions 21 to 24.\n\nAnnouncer | 16:31 Now listen to the first part of the discussion and answer questions 21 to 24.\n\nTutor | 16:39 We're very pleased to welcome Professor Isaac Nebworth to our tutorial group today and he's come to share one of his pet passions with us, city traffic and our western dependence on the motor car.\n\nTutor | 16:51 I believe questions are quite welcome throughout. I know you're all very familiar with the superhighway here in Melbourne, but do super highways automatically lead to super wealth as our politicians would have us believe? I think not.\n\nStudent 1 | 17:08 Can you give us an example of what you mean exactly?\n\nProfessor | 17:11 Sure. Well, by continuing to encourage this dependence on the motorcar, we simply create more congestion and «more urban sprawl». And you can see that here in Melbourne, right under your nose.\n\nStudent 2 | 17:23 Excuse me. I would just like to say that I feel the sprawl is part of the city.\n\nStudent 2 | 17:29 The freeways mean «people can enjoy the benefits of living away from the center» on larger blocks with gardens but still be able to drive back into the city center for work or entertainment.\n\nProfessor | 17:40 Well, I'm not convinced that people want to do that. And is our money being well spent? It may be okay for you now, but come back to me in 5 years time.\n\nProfessor | 17:51 Let's take City Link for example. the new freeway.\n\nStudent 2 | 17:54 The freeway all the time. I think it's great.\n\nProfessor | 17:56 Ah, yes, but it cost $2 billion to build. And you could have gotten 10 times the value by putting the money into public transport.\n\nProfessor | 18:03 If you give the automobile road space, it will fill that space. And «you'll soon find you'll be crawling along your city link».\n\nStudent 1 | 18:13 But surely you cannot simply blame the car. Some of the blame must rest with governments and city planners.\n\nStudent 2 | 18:20 Well, there is an argument that building good roads is actually beneficial because most new cars these days are highly efficient.\n\nStudent 2 | 18:26 «They use far less petrol than in the past» and emissions of dangerous gases are low.\n\nStudent 2 | 18:33 «Old congested roads, on the other hand, encourage traffic to move slowly and it's the stationary cars that cause the pollution and smog». Whereas good roads increase traffic speeds and thus the amount of time cars are actually on the roads.\n\nProfessor | 18:46 Well, this is the old argument put forward by the road lobby, but for me it's clearcut equals smog. Public transport is the way to go.\n\nAnnouncer | 18:59 In the second part of the discussion, the professor talks about public transport in different cities.\n\nAnnouncer | 19:06 Look at questions 25 to 30 first.\n\nAnnouncer | 19:51 As you listen to the discussion, complete the questions about public transport.\n\nTutor | 19:58 Now, on the topic of public transport, I read somewhere recently that Australia isn't doing too badly in the challenge to increase the use of public transport.\n\nProfessor | 20:07 Better than America, granted, but by comparison with Canada, it's not so good.\n\nProfessor | 20:12 For instance, if you compare Toronto with the US metropolis of Detroit, only 160 km away. In Detroit, only 1% of passenger travel is by public transport. Whereas in Toronto, it's 24%.\n\nStudent 1 | 20:28 Which is considerably better than Sydney, which can only boast 16%.\n\nStudent 2 | 20:33 Well, I think it's encouraging that our least car dependent city is actually our largest city. «16% of trips being taken on public transport in Sydney isn't too bad,»\n\nProfessor | 20:43 but it's a long way behind Europe. Take both London and Paris for instance, where third on public transport.\n\nStudent 1 | 20:50 Well, they do both have an excellent underground system,\n\nProfessor | 20:53 and« Frankfurt comes in higher still at 32%».\n\nStudent 2 | 20:56 I understand that they've been very successful in Copenhagen at ridding the city of the car. Can you tell us anything about that experiment?\n\nProfessor | 21:04 Yes, indeed. Copenhagen is a wonderful example of a city that has learned to live without the motorcar.\n\nProfessor | 21:08 Back in the 1960s, they adopted a number of policies designed to draw people back into the city. «For instance, they paid musicians and artists to perform in the streets.» They also built cycle lanes.\n\nProfessor | 21:20 And now 30% of the inhabitants of Copenhagen use a bicycle to go to work. Sydney, by comparison, can only boast 1% of the population cycling to work.\n\nStudent 1 | 21:33 It could have something to do with all the hills.\n\nProfessor | 21:36 Then they banned cars from many parts of the city. «And every year, 3% of the city parking is removed.»\n\nProfessor | 21:41 And by constantly reducing parking, they've created public spaces and also freely available bicycles, which you can hire for practically nothing. And of course, they have an excellent public transport system.\n\nStudent 2 | 21:55 Well, that's all very well for Copenhagen, but I'd just like to say that some cities are just too large for a decent public transport system to work well, particularly in areas with low population, «because if there aren't many people using the service, then they don't schedule enough buses or trains for that route.»\n\nStudent 1 | 22:13 I accept that there is a vicious circle here, but people do need to support the system.\n\nStudent 1 | 22:18 And secondly, «the whole process takes so long because usually you have to change. »You know, from bus to train, that sort of thing. And that can be quite difficult. Ultimately, it's much easier to jump in your car. And often it turns out to be cheaper.\n\nProfessor | 22:33 Sure. But cheaper for whom? You or society?\n\nProfessor | 22:35 We have to work towards the ideal and not give in all the time because things are too difficult. Anyway, let's move on to some of the results of\n\nAnnouncer | 23:01 That is the end of part three.\n\nAnnouncer | 23:05 You now have 30 seconds to check your answers to part three."],"listening-w5-classwork":["PART 1: Transport Survey\n\nAnnouncer | 0:44 Part one,\n\nAnnouncer | 0:47 you will hear a man interviewing a woman in the street about her use of transport.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:54 First, you have some time to look at questions 1 to Five.\n\n(Khoảng nghỉ từ 0:56 đến 1:35)\n\nAnnouncer | 1:35 Now we shall begin. You should answer the questions as you listen because you will not hear the recording a second time.\n\nAnnouncer | 1:45 Listen carefully and answer questions one to five.\n\nInterviewer | 1:53 Excuse me.\n\nLouisa | 1:54 Yes.\n\nInterviewer | 1:54 I wonder if you could spare a few minutes to do a survey on transport. It won't take long. Uh,\n\nLouisa | 2:00 no, that's fine.\n\nInterviewer | 2:01 Oh, lovely. The survey is on behalf of the local council. They'd like to know about what transport you use and any suggestions for improvement. Uh, can I start by asking you how you travel to town today?\n\nLouisa | 2:16 Sure. I came on the bus.\n\nInterviewer | 2:18 Great. Now, can I get a few details about yourself?\n\nLouisa | 2:22 Okay.\n\nInterviewer | 2:23 What's your name?\n\nLouisa | 2:24 It's Louisa.\n\nInterviewer | 2:26 Yes.\n\nLouisa | 2:26 Hardy.\n\nInterviewer | 2:27 Can you spell that, please?\n\nLouisa | 2:29 Yes, it's «H A R D I E».\n\nInterviewer | 2:33 Great. Thanks. And can I have your address?\n\nLouisa | 2:37 It's «19 White Stone Road».\n\nInterviewer | 2:40 Oh, right. I know that area. It's Bradfield, isn't it?\n\nLouisa | 2:44 That's right.\n\nInterviewer | 2:45 Is the post code GT7?\n\nLouisa | 2:48 It's actually «GT82LC».\n\nInterviewer | 2:51 Great. And could I ask what your job is? Are you a student?\n\nLouisa | 2:55 I've actually just finished my training. I'm a «hairdresser».\n\nInterviewer | 2:59 Oh, right. And one more question in this section. What is the reason for you coming into town today?\n\nLouisa | 3:06 Actually, it's not for shopping today, which would be my normal reason, uh, but to see the «dentist».\n\nInterviewer | 3:11 Right. Thanks.\n\nAnnouncer | 3:15 Before you hear the rest of the interview, you have some time to look at questions 6 to 10.\n\n(Khoảng nghỉ từ 3:23 đến 3:50)\n\nAnnouncer | 3:50 Now listen and answer questions 6 to 10.\n\nInterviewer | 3:57 Now in this last section, I'd like you to give us some ideas about the facilities and arrangements in the city for getting to and from work. Um, any suggestions you have for improvements?\n\nLouisa | 4:11 Well, something I've thought about for some time is that when I walk and I'm doing a later shift, I think the lighting should be better.\n\nInterviewer | 4:21 Yes, good point.\n\nLouisa | 4:22 And of course, I think it's a real shame they've been cutting down on the number of «footpaths». They should have more of those.\n\nInterviewer | 4:28 Then people would walk more.\n\nLouisa | 4:30 Yes. Right.\n\nLouisa | 4:31 And I don't think there are enough «trains». That's why I don't use them. you have to wait so long.\n\nInterviewer | 4:37 Thanks. And finally, I'd like to ask your opinion on cycling. As you may know, there's a drive in the city to get more people to cycle to work,\n\nLouisa | 4:46 right?\n\nInterviewer | 4:47 But we realize that there are things which the council, but also employers might do to help encourage workers to cycle to work.\n\nLouisa | 4:54 Yeah. Well, I have thought about it and where I work, there are no safe places to leave your «bikes».\n\nLouisa | 5:01 Okay. And also, I'd have to cycle uphill. And on a hot day, I'd arrive at work pretty sweaty. So, I think I'd need a «shower» somewhere at work,\n\nInterviewer | 5:10 right?\n\nLouisa | 5:11 And I suppose the last thing is that I wouldn't be all that confident about cycling on such «busy» roads.\n\nLouisa | 5:18 I think I'd like to see you offering training for that. You know, I'd feel a lot better about starting if that was the case.\n\nInterviewer | 5:25 Well, that's very helpful. Uh, thank you very much for your time.\n\nLouisa | 5:29 No problem. Bye.\n\nAnnouncer | 5:46 That is the end of part one.\n\nAnnouncer | 5:50 You now have one minute to check your answers to part one.","PART 2: Kingtown Council Event Review\n\nAnnouncer | 06:58 Part two.\n\nAnnouncer | 07:04 You will hear the public relations officer from the council reviewing events that were hosted by the town in the previous year.\n\nAnnouncer | 07:12 First, you have some time to look at questions 11 to 16.\n\n(Khoảng nghỉ từ 07:14 đến 07:37)\n\nAnnouncer | 07:37 Listen carefully and answer questions 11 to 16.\n\nOfficer | 07:43 Kingtown has been a busy town this year with some high-profile and new events happening in and around the area.\n\nOfficer | 07:52 In January, we hosted the «National Kayak Selections». And this competition attracted a number of well-known «paddlers», not just from this country, but from Canada, Ireland, England, and Australia.\n\nOfficer | 08:05 Following this event, we had the nation's top« bowls players» descend on the township with the national championships taking place at the Kingtown Bowling Club, attracting well over 400 players.\n\nOfficer | 08:16 It was a resounding success, as you could see from the numbers, thronging the bowling center in Main Street.\n\nOfficer | 08:26 February was the month for the serious social rafting competition and this was the first time Kingtown had hosted an event of this nature. It attracted 96 paddlers from all walks of life who enjoyed «a great day of fun on the river.»\n\nOfficer | 08:44 After the success of last year's open half marathon event, this year in March, we hosted a women's only «duathlon» in an attempt to get more women involved in sport.\n\nOfficer | 08:55 The starting point was at the Kingtown pool, but an extremely chilly evening saw a huge reduction in the numbers we were expecting.\n\nOfficer | 09:05 However, approximately 50 participants were not deterred from tackling the event, which for many was the first time. «And these hardy contestants went into the first 2.5k run with great enthusiasm.»\n\nOfficer | 09:20 The cycle leg was extremely challenging because it was into a headwind all the way and the last 5k run was no easier.\n\nOfficer | 09:29 At this point, I must thank all the volunteers who took time out to help make this event successful, especially the road marshals who did an excellent job.\n\nOfficer | 09:39 We must also thank the Kingtown Creative Pursuits Society for hosting the wonderful autumn festival.\n\nOfficer | 09:44 The women involved put on a magnificent demonstration of traditional and present-day «craft work »ranging from ancient weaving techniques to modern «pottery designs and sculpture».\n\nOfficer | 09:59 These ladies are highly skilled and they got a good turnout on the day which by the way they are thinking of making a biannual event. So, we might have a spring festival on its way.\n\nOfficer | 10:10 Winter brought with it the annual Kingdown Youth Tournament, which was a huge success with the allocated team slots filling up fast.\n\nOfficer | 10:21 Teams consisted of approximately 15 youths ranging in age from 8 to 18. «The teams spent the day on the fields of Prince Park playing a round-robin touch tournament system.»\n\nOfficer | 10:37 The event, which drew large crowds of the public who cheered and gave lots of support and encouragement for the teams, showcased some outstanding youth talent.\n\nAnnouncer | 10:49 Before you hear the rest of the talk, you have some time to look at questions 17 to 20.\n\n(Khoảng nghỉ từ 10:54 đến 11:16)\n\nAnnouncer | 11:16 Now listen and answer questions 17 to 20.\n\nOfficer | 11:22 Now what's coming up for the school holidays?\n\nOfficer | 11:26 Well, the town council has several plans lined up to keep the kids busy. Let's get straight into it.\n\nOfficer | 11:31 Program one, which will take place around the Prince Park area, has a sports agenda and will have participants engaged in a variety of sporting activities such as tennis, athletics, «football», and «swimming».\n\nOfficer | 11:49 Program two is for the somewhat less active and more creative children. They will do most of their activities in and around the Lord Hall area.\n\nOfficer | 12:01 These will consist of «cooking», craft, «dance», and «hair styling». You'd be surprised at the number of children who leap at the chance to learn to cook, not to mention the other activities.\n\nOfficer | 12:11 The hall will be positively buzzing, I can tell you. This is a great chance for your children to learn a new skill or brush up on one that they're already crazy about.\n\nOfficer | 12:24 Program three is for the more adventurous children. Because of this, we do insist on a minimum age limit of 11 years old.\n\nOfficer | 12:33 The Duke Recreational Area has been set aside for this program. Expect your youngsters to learn a lot about leadership and teamwork as they accomplish some of their missions.\n\nOfficer | 12:47 They'll engage in activities such as «skateboarding», «rafting», «orientering», «mountain biking», and «trekking».\n\nOfficer | 12:56 Well, thank you for your attention. If you have any questions, please feel free to ask.\n\nAnnouncer | 13:12 That is the end of part two.\n\nAnnouncer | 13:16 You now have 30 seconds to check your answers to part two.","PART 3: Presentation on Woolly Mammoths\n\nAnnouncer | 13:52 part three.\n\nAnnouncer | 14:01 You will hear two environmental science students called Rosie and Martin discussing their presentation on an extinct animal called the woolly mammoth with their tutor.\n\nAnnouncer | 14:15 First, you have some time to look at questions 21 to 24.\n\n(Khoảng nghỉ từ 14:18 đến 14:53)\n\nAnnouncer | 14:53 Now listen carefully and answer questions 21 to 24.\n\nTutor | 15:02 So Rosie and Martin, let's look at what you've got for your presentation on woolly mammoths.\n\nRosie | 15:10 Okay, we've got a short outline here.\n\nTutor | 15:14 Thanks. Uh, so it's about a research project in North America.\n\nRosie | 15:21 Yes. But we thought we needed something general about woolly mammoths in our introduction to establish that they were related to our modern elephant and they lived thousands of years ago in the last ice age.\n\nMartin | 15:36 Maybe we could show a video clip of a cartoon about mammoths, but that would be a bit childish. Or «we could have a diagram. »It could be a «timeline» to show when they lived with illustrations.\n\nRosie | 15:51 Or we could just show a drawing of them walking in the ice.\n\nTutor | 15:54 No, let's go with «your last suggestion».\n\nTutor | 15:59 Good. Then you're describing the discovery of the mammoth tooth on St. Paul's Island in Alaska and why it was significant.\n\nRosie | 16:10 Yes. The tooth was found by a man called Russell Graham. He picked it up from under a rock in a cave. He knew it was special.\n\nRosie | 16:20 For a start, it was in really good condition, as if it had been just extracted from the animal's jawbone. Anyway, they found it was 6,500 years old.\n\nTutor | 16:34 So, why was that significant?\n\nMartin | 16:38 Well, the mammoth bones previously found on the North American mainland were «much less recent» than that. So, this was really amazing.\n\nMartin | 16:48 Then, we're making an animated diagram to show the geography of the area in prehistoric times.\n\nMartin | 16:54 So, originally St. Paul's Island wasn't an island. It was connected to the mainland and mammoths and other animals like bears were able to roam around the whole area.\n\nRosie | 17:10 Then the climate warmed up and the sea level began to rise and «the island got cut off from the mainland». So those mammoths on the island couldn't escape.\n\nRosie | 17:22 They had to stay on the island. And in fact, the species survived there for thousands of years after they'd become extinct on the mainland.\n\nTutor | 17:33 So why do you think they died out on the mainland?\n\nRosie | 17:37 No one's sure.\n\nMartin | 17:39 Anyway, next we'll explain how Graham and his team identified the date when the mammoths became extinct on the island.\n\nMartin | 17:47 They concluded that the extinction happened 5,600 years ago, which «is a very precise time »for a prehistoric extinction.\n\nRosie | 17:59 It's based on samples they took from mud at the bottom of a lake on the island. They analyzed it to find out what had fallen in over time.\n\nRosie | 18:07 Bits of plants, volcanic ash, and even DNA from the mammoth themselves. It's standard procedure, but it took nearly 2 years to do.\n\nAnnouncer | 18:23 Before you hear the rest of the discussion, you have some time to look at questions 25 to 30.\n\n(Khoảng nghỉ từ 18:28 đến 19:03)\n\nAnnouncer | 19:03 Now listen and answer questions 25 to 30.\n\nTutor | 19:11 So why don't you quickly go through the main sections of your presentation and discuss what actions needed for each part.\n\nRosie | 19:20 Okay. So for the introduction, we're using a visual. So once we've prepared that, we're done.\n\nMartin | 19:28 I'm not sure. I think we need to «write down all the ideas we want to include here», not just rely on memory. How we begin the presentation is so important.\n\nRosie | 19:40 You're right.\n\nMartin | 19:41 The discovery of the mammoth tooth is probably the most dramatic part, but we don't have that much information. only what we got from the online article.\n\nMartin | 19:53 I thought maybe we could get in touch with« the researcher who led the team »and ask him to tell us a bit more.\n\nRosie | 20:00 Great idea. What about the section with the initial questions asked by the researchers? We've got a lot on that, but we need to make it interesting.\n\nMartin | 20:11 «We could ask the audience» to suggest some questions about it and then see how many of them we can answer. I don't think it would take too long.\n\nRosie | 20:21 Yes, that would add a bit of variety.\n\nRosie | 20:24 Then the section on further research carried out on the island, analyzing the mud in the lake. I wonder if we've actually got too much information here. Should we cut some?\n\nMartin | 20:37 I don't think so, but it's all a bit muddled at present.\n\nRosie | 20:42 Yes, maybe it would be better «if it followed a chronological pattern.»\n\nMartin | 20:46 I think so. The findings and possible explanations section is just about ready, but «we need to practice it so we're sure it won't overrun».\n\nRosie | 20:56 I think it should be okay. But yes, let's make sure.\n\nTutor | 21:01 H in the last section, relevance to the present day. You've got some good ideas, but this is where you need to move away from the ideas of others and «give your own viewpoint».\n\nRosie | 21:14 Okay, we'll think about that. Now, shall we show you some of the\n\nAnnouncer | 21:33 end of part three.\n\nAnnouncer | 21:36 You now have 30 seconds to check your answers to part three."],"listening-w6-classwork":["PART 1: Antique Shop Complaint & Order\n\nAnnouncer | 0:01 This is the IELTS listening test.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:05 You will hear a number of different recordings and you will have to answer questions on what you hear.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:13 There will be time for you to read the instructions and questions and you will have a chance to check your work.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:21 All the recordings will be played once only.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:25 The test is in four parts.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:29 At the end of the test, you will be given 10 minutes to transfer your answers to the answer sheet.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:37 Now, turn to part one.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:44 Part one.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:51 You will hear a woman phoning an antique shop complaining about the delivery service and some damage to the item she purchased.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:59 First, you have some time to look at questions 1 to four.\n\n(Khoảng nghỉ từ 1:01 đến 1:33)\n\nAnnouncer | 1:33 You will see that there is an example which has been done for you. On this occasion only, the conversation relating to this will be played first.\n\nStaff | 1:44 Hello, this is the complaint center of the service department Antiques. Before we start, I'll just need to take more details from you. Okay.\n\nAnna | 1:53 Sure, no problem.\n\nStaff | 1:54 Well, could you please tell me your full name, madam?\n\nAnna | 1:57 It is Anna Lumley. That's Anna. L U M L E Y.\n\nAnnouncer | 2:04 The caller's name is Anna Lumley. So, Anna Lumley has been written in the space. Now, we shall begin. You should answer the questions as you listen because you will not hear the recording a second time. Listen carefully and answer questions 1 to 4.\n\nStaff | 2:25 Hello, this is the complaint center of the service department at Clifton Antiques. Before we start, I'll just need to take more details from you. Okay.\n\nAnna | 2:34 Sure, no problem.\n\nStaff | 2:36 Well, could you please tell me your full name, madam?\n\nAnna | 2:38 It is Anna Lumley. That's Anna. L U M L E Y.\n\nStaff | 2:44 All right. L U M O E Y.\n\nAnna | 2:47 Not exactly. The fourth letter is L, not O.\n\nStaff | 2:52 Oh, sorry. Let me rewrite it. And may I have your contact number that we can use to reach you during the week?\n\nAnna | 2:58 Sure. My mobile phone number is «077876345».\n\nStaff | 3:06 Great. Now, what can I do for you today, Anna?\n\nAnna | 3:08 I placed an order for a large quantity of items with you last week on the «20th of February» and had been expecting them to« arrive at the office in a week». However, only half of the shipment has been delivered. I would just like to ensure that they haven't gone missing in transit.\n\nStaff | 3:27 All right, madam. It's a pity we have caused this inconvenience to you. I'll look for the parcel track record and see if I can give you a date when you should receive the rest of your order. What was your delivery address listed?\n\nAnna | 3:39 I made the arrangements for the parcel to be conveyed from your warehouse on road to my office address at 235 Arandelle Road.\n\nStaff | 3:50 Sorry, could you say it again? The address?\n\nAnna | 3:52 235 Arandale Road. «A K E N D A L E» in East Sea.\n\nStaff | 4:02 Yes, sir. Well, okay. Our system has tracked your parcel which shows that your shipment has been received. However, there's no record about the lost items. I would suggest that you wait for 2 days and if the other items don't arrive, then you might need to consider to claim insurance coverage for the value of the rest. How much are they worth?\n\nAnna | 4:22 Um, they cost me $34,500 in total.\n\nStaff | 4:27 All right. For this amount, I think 10% will be covered by the insurance company. Therefore, you could claim« $3,450 »from them if you'd like to. There is a form on our website that you can fill in, and when the loss is confirmed, you'll get the money within five working days. The rest of the money will be refunded to you in a month, so you won't suffer a financial loss.\n\nAnna | 4:48 It sounds reasonable.\n\nAnnouncer | 4:53 Before you hear the rest of the conversation, you have some time to look at questions 5 to 10.\n\n(Khoảng nghỉ từ 4:57 đến 5:28)\n\nAnnouncer | 5:28 Now listen and answer questions 5 to 10.\n\nStaff | 5:34 Yet it is necessary to make a list of your lost items so we can reach it against our records. Is that okay?\n\nAnna | 5:41 Of course. Okay. It is unfortunate that a few of the missing items are one of a kind and thus irreplaceable. Also, there were many small items that aren't very valuable, like lamps and chairs. However, there was a large item of antique furniture and «a bag filled with first edition books,» which was some of the first ever to be printed on a press.\n\nStaff | 6:04 Right. Okay. Anything else?\n\nAnna | 6:07 Yeah, there was also some important items. a Victorian rocking chair for my daughter, «some large oil paintings originating from the Edwwardian period», and a few decorative fruit bowls.\n\nStaff | 6:20 Right. Okay. I've taken down the list of these missing items, so I'll call the warehouse to see if any of them are still there.\n\nAnna | 6:27 Ah, I almost forgot. There are several other pieces that I've spotted on your website and wanted to order. May I do that now?\n\nStaff | 6:34 It is definitely okay. Would you tell me a little about the items that you're looking to buy?\n\nAnna | 6:39 There is a gold clock and «a golden framed vintage mirror.»\n\nStaff | 6:43 Okay, perfect. The charge will be taken from the payment card that you used before. You can expect them to be delivered within the next week. Is there anything else that I can do for you today?\n\nAnna | 6:54 Yes, I received two damaged items in the shipment. So, I need to claim for a partial refund.\n\nStaff | 7:00 Oh, sorry. I need to know more about the details of the actual damage over the phone line before you put in a full report. What kinds of pieces are damaged?\n\nAnna | 7:09 «A drawer is missing from the antique mahogany desk», and I also spotted a dent on one of the corners, so it's basically unusable.\n\nStaff | 7:18 I see. Do you know how much it will cost to repair it?\n\nAnna | 7:22 No. Well, I don't think it's repairable. I will have to buy a new one.\n\nStaff | 7:27 Sorry. I'll take a note of that and see what we can do for compensation. Anything else?\n\nAnna | 7:32 I also purchased of dining chairs with navy leather padding. However, the color is faded and «one of the legs has completely split down the middle.»\n\nStaff | 7:41 Okay. Are there any other damaged pieces?\n\nAnna | 7:44 Yes, there is a set of Chinese crockery to furnish my dining room table, but when I opened the case, I found that a cup was lost and that «some plates had smashed. Four, actually.»\n\nStaff | 7:56 And is that all of the items?\n\nAnna | 7:58 Yes, I think that's all.\n\nStaff | 8:00 Right. I'll estimate the value of the damage and a refund will be issued.\n\nAnna | 8:05 Okay. Cheers for your great help.\n\nStaff | 8:07 No problem. My pleasure. Goodbye.\n\nAnnouncer | 8:39 That is the end of part one.\n\nAnnouncer | 8:42 You now have one minute to check your answers to part one.","PART 2: Trelloar Valley Tour Guide\n\nAnnouncer | 09:50 Part two,\n\nAnnouncer | 09:54 you will hear part of a broadcast for tourists about the popular holiday region called the Trelloar Valley.\n\nAnnouncer | 10:02 First, you have some time to look at questions 11 to 14.\n\n(Khoảng nghỉ từ 10:04 đến 10:35)\n\nAnnouncer | 10:35 Now listen carefully and answer questions 11 to 14.\n\nGuide | 10:42 An unspoiled splendid scenery takes its shape in the valley and estuaries of the river Trelloar.\n\nGuide | 10:50 Abundant with wildlife as well as views of historic interest, there are lots of channels to explore the area with the wonderful public transport networks.\n\nGuide | 10:57 With just short walks in between spots, it is possible for you to leave the car behind and travel by boat, train or bus.\n\nGuide | 11:05 There is the Trelloar Valley passenger ferry running between villages alongside the river Eststerie and serves as a link with the train station at Barry from which it takes only a 10-minute walk from the riverside village of Carlton.\n\nGuide | 11:17 In the past, the main transport way in the area was the river. And as in the past, the ferry timetable varied from day to day according to the time and height of the tide.\n\nGuide | 11:28 The ferry is also seasonal, usually running its business during the period «between April and September» depending on the weather.\n\nGuide | 11:34 Visiting our website www.trillorferryy.co.uk, it's convenient to download the timetable.\n\nGuide | 11:42 If you would like to relax and enjoy the wonderful scenery, just take a river cruise to Carlton and back from the nearby city of Plymouth.\n\nGuide | 11:48 Visitors were carried along the same route by steam ships in the past. Queen Victoria and her family also enjoyed such a trip in 1856.\n\nGuide | 11:56 Today, it takes you a few hours to make the journey. The round trip only lasts for 4 to 5 hours, varying in terms of the tides and weather.\n\nGuide | 12:06 You can travel up river by boat and «return to Plymouth by train» if you prefer. There will be wheelchair access on all the cruise boats and trains.\n\nGuide | 12:14 For more information and departure times, please ring Plymouth Boat Cruise on 01752823104.\n\nGuide | 12:21 Trains travel between Carlton and Plymouth many times a day with different stations in between throughout the year. Local commuters as well as visitors who fancy the lovely scenery prefer to use the service.\n\nGuide | 12:33 The highlight of the journey is going across the river on the amazing «viaduct» which was constructed in the early period of the 20th century and« it towers 120 ft over the water».\n\nGuide | 12:44 Tickets can be directly bought on the train so it is unnecessary to book ahead. You can reach national rail inquiries by phone or online for more details about fairs and times.\n\nGuide | 12:52 The bus service is now linking all train stations and villages in the zone especially for holiday makers.\n\nGuide | 13:01 There is a Rover ticket including unlimited journeys which can be used on weekends and national holidays.\n\nGuide | 13:08 The Rover ticket offers great value for money and is now «even cheaper than it was last year». For adults, a ticket costs £550 per day. For senior citizens, the cost is £450 and a family ticket for up to five people only costs £12. You can purchase tickets on the bus.\n\nAnnouncer | 13:28 Before you hear the rest of the talk, you have some time to look at questions 15 to 20.\n\n(Khoảng nghỉ từ 13:32 đến 14:02)\n\nAnnouncer | 14:02 Now listen and answer questions 15 to 20.\n\nGuide | 14:08 At the center of the Trillor estuary area is the historic riverside village of Colton.\n\nGuide | 14:15 The main road comes into the village from the south. And for those who are riding by bus, it turns «left just before the bridge and stops in the layby on the left» hand side.\n\nGuide | 14:24 From there, it's just a short walk to Carlton's various attractions.\n\nGuide | 14:28 If you're arriving by car, you have to leave it in the main car park. «Go over the bridge, take the first turn on the right, then go on until you come to the end of that road.» It's the only place to park in Carlton, but there's no charge.\n\nGuide | 14:41 If you're interested in Lok Street, there's a museum in Carlton with farming, fishing, and household implements from the late 19th century.\n\nGuide | 14:49 As you come in from the south,« cross the river and go straight on the same road until you reach the end».\n\nGuide | 14:56 Also on the subject of history, you can go and see the old mill, which has recently been renovated and put back into use.\n\nGuide | 15:01 «Turn left before you come to the bridge». Then go straight on and take the« first turning on the right.» This leads straight there.\n\nGuide | 15:08 If you're interested in arts and crafts, there's a potter's studio where you can watch the artist at work.\n\nGuide | 15:15 «After crossing the bridge, turn left and it's the second building on the left.»\n\nGuide | 15:19 Finally, when you're in need of refreshments,« there's a cafe opposite the old boat house» and a picnic area near the mill.\n\nAnnouncer | 15:49 That is the end of part two.\n\nAnnouncer | 15:52 You now have 30 seconds to check your answers to part two.","PART 3: Research Methodology Seminar\n\nAnnouncer | 16:28 Part three.\n\nAnnouncer | 16:32 You will hear two students who are taking a research methodology course. A girl called Laya and a boy called Jake are having a seminar with their tutor.\n\nAnnouncer | 16:43 First, you have some time to look at questions 21 to 24.\n\n(Khoảng nghỉ từ 16:45 đến 17:17)\n\nAnnouncer | 17:17 Now listen carefully and answer questions 21 to 24.\n\nTutor | 17:24 So I gave you both a task to select an article about a small scale research project.\n\nLaya | 17:29 Yes.\n\nJake | 17:30 Yes. And I required you to have a trial to replicate the procedures of the research in your own context. I mean try it out yourself.\n\nLaya | 17:36 Yeah. And we've done that.\n\nTutor | 17:39 Nice. In this way, I want you to tell me a little bit about the article and explain why it started applying crosswords to assist the students to review the exam terminologies.\n\nJake | 17:50 All right. The article was written by two university professors who had initially used crosswords to help the students revise the terminology for exams.\n\nLaya | 18:00 And the crosswords were designed and installed on computers. And we selected the article because though we weren't familiar with the technique,« it seems an accessible topic». You know, using it to design crosswords for higher education.\n\nTutor | 18:14 That's a good reason. So, both of the professors would like to see how well this innovation was received by their students.\n\nJake | 18:21 Yes.\n\nLaya | 18:22 Yes.\n\nTutor | 18:22 So, what has been going on with your reproducing the research?\n\nJake | 18:26 Well, we collected some terms from our own modules and put them in a list. Then we designed a crossword to revise them.\n\nLaya | 18:35 Then we invited some of our classmates to try out our crossword and then asked for some feedback from them. You know, like their feelings, views, as well as some suggestions about using this technique.\n\nTutor | 18:45 Did you find it easy to have people participate in it?\n\nJake | 18:47 Not really. First you know it was actually hard but later when we convinced them by talking about the actual benefit that they will get from participating in this research on «preparing for an exam which is coming up» later this semester it functioned great.\n\nTutor | 19:04 So how did you get the feedback from the students that tells you their thoughts about the crosswords by a questionnaire?\n\nLaya | 19:10 There were two pages in the original questionnaire and it included lots of XL questions, but the whole section about difficulties using it is now« out of date». Even the questionnaire had just been finished a few years ago.\n\nTutor | 19:23 So, have you done a version?\n\nJake | 19:26 Sure. And then we emailed it to 40 students and received 28 replies. I was disappointed by the fact, but this was a relatively good result.\n\nJake | 19:37 I mean, the responses we got from them were well written. You know, people did take a lot of care with them,« but I was still taken aback with the low numbers.»\n\nTutor | 19:46 Yes, for an apprentice researcher, it's an important lesson to learn.\n\nLaya | 19:50 Yeah.\n\nAnnouncer | 19:54 Before you hear the rest of the talk, you have some time to look at questions 25 to 30.\n\n(Khoảng nghỉ từ 19:58 đến 20:29)\n\nAnnouncer | 20:29 Now listen and answer questions 25 to 30.\n\nTutor | 20:36 So what was your result?\n\nJake | 20:39 Well, basically their feedback was extremely positive. The students said that crosswords on a computer really helped them «not to get distracted and stay focused» on the work in hand, which is better than other ways of doing the revision that are often disturbed by other things.\n\nLaya | 20:54 Yeah, that was really clear. But I was struck by the fact that they hardly featured having fun in their responses, nor did anything to do with spelling of hard words, which I thought would apparently be a benefit.\n\nJake | 21:07 No. Okay. The responses also said that the crosswords hadn't really prompted their general motivation to study, but« it had highlighted the gaps in their memory, so they could figure out what kind of work was necessary to do fair.»\n\nTutor | 21:21 Right. So, how did your findings compare with those done by the original researchers?\n\nLaya | 21:25 There were a couple of similarities, but we still found two primary differences. «Compared with females, more males like the technique. Yet, the original findings were the reverse case.»\n\nJake | 21:38 Also,« our respondents said they wouldn't mind doing a crossword in the final official exam. Even in the original study, it showed that even if crossword makes exams shorter, they would not like it to be included.»\n\nLaya | 21:50 But for informal purposes, of course, both sets of respondents said doing more crosswords would be of great interest to them, like revision and so on.\n\nTutor | 22:00 Right. So, let's think about the whole project and what you've learned from it.\n\nJake | 22:04 Well, it really took a long time.\n\nLaya | 22:07 Yeah. And I don't think we handled that aspect well.\n\nJake | 22:10 It could have gone worse. I mean, there was not much data collected, so we didn't have to spend ages dealing with it. And since we'd already done numerical data processing, there wasn't much new for us.\n\nLaya | 22:23 Yeah, definitely. Anyway, I think the questions «we designed were good so that the data we collected was manageable.»\n\nJake | 22:30 Yeah, it really helped having the original study to guide us as it were and that helped us to see what a good instrument research is.\n\nLaya | 22:39 What questionnaires should be like?\n\nJake | 22:41 Absolutely.« We got a lot from that». But when we were writing up the project, we weren't sure on how to acknowledge the work of the original study. You know, our referencing. No, that's what we both need to learn in the future.\n\nLaya | 22:55 Actually, that part's been great. «Finding ways to share and support another person.»\n\nJake | 23:00 That's« the real plus from the project», learning ways to do that.\n\nTutor | 23:04 Well, it's obviously been very successful.\n\nAnnouncer | 23:23 That is the end of part three.\n\nAnnouncer | 23:26 You now have 30 seconds to check your answers to part three."],"listening-w7-classwork":["Transcript\n\nNarrator | 00:00 Part four, you will hear a lecture about airport design. First, you have some time to look at questions 31 to 40.\n\nNarrator | 01:09 Now listen carefully and answer questions 31 to 40.\n\nLecturer | 01:17 Good morning everyone. Well, last week we looked at some of the architectural features of modern house design and today we're going to move on to look at airport design and how this has changed over the years.\n\nLecturer | 01:34 So, if we start by going back to, um, the 1960s and ’70s when there were a lot fewer airports than there are today, well, check-in desks, customs, and waiting areas were all very basic. They were rather like a «bus station»«(Q31)», uh, designed to allow air traffic in and out of the terminal, but not very welcoming for passengers. Even though passengers spent a lot of time there, the important features were related to the flights rather than the people who took them or indeed the places where the airports were built.\n\nLecturer | 02:11 But that all changed in the next few decades. And if you look at any big airport now, it’s more like a mini «city»«(Q32)». It combines a transport center with a mall full of shops and facilities designed to make passengers feel more comfortable. So, airports have been transformed. And as with any city building, their design now takes into account features outside the airport terminal as well.\n\nLecturer | 02:40 So, why did this change happen? Well, there are two main reasons. The first was the huge increase in passenger numbers—in the number of people traveling by plane. And this was a direct result of «mass tourism»«(Q33)» with things like, um, cheap holiday packages and low-cost airlines with the construction of high-rise hotels and hotel complexes. And then people started traveling more regularly from one country to another for things like meetings. And so the growth in «international business»«(Q34)» also pushed numbers up. In fact, passenger growth has been so significant over the past 30 years that it’s estimated that some 21st-century airports will need to handle up to 50 million passengers a year by 2020.\n\nLecturer | 03:35 The second reason for the change is—and this is a key aspect of airport design—people have realized that the airport is the first place you see when you visit another country. This means it forms your first impression of that country and that «impression»«(Q35)» has to be good. Airports are now called gateways to the cities they serve and that raises visitor expectations.\n\nLecturer | 04:02 Now what are the changes that have taken place in airport design? Well, the interior design, the inside of most airports, is now completely different. First, the dark enclosed airports of the past have been replaced by large «open areas»«(Q36)» that look out onto the surroundings. Look at this picture of Beijing airport. There’s a huge amount of space and light and this is typical of many airports today.\n\nLecturer | 04:33 Second, well, in the past, you had to go outside the airport to get trains to terminals, but now these are integrated into the design. Also, airport walkways are wide and can cope with the large volume of people—people who want to feel calm and relaxed, who want to get around the airport easily. In this way, the «stress»«(Q37)» of modern travel has been minimized.\n\nLecturer | 05:01 Outside, the buildings have changed, too. Airports were once ugly buildings with large towers and concrete boxes around them. Now, they’re designed to fit into their surroundings. Look at this picture of the Arctic Circle Airport in Norway. The airport itself is surrounded by mountains. So, as you can see, the «roof»«(Q38)» of the airport has been designed so that it’s shaped like a range of mountains. There are peaks at the top and then steep sides that touch the ground.\n\nLecturer | 05:35 In the same way, these airports in Thailand and India have beautiful «shaded gardens»«(Q39)» all around them that reflect the landscape of the country. They also provide a connection with local tradition and art. Another feature that is important inside airports, too.\n\nLecturer | 05:56 And there's one final but very important issue. It’s been said that airports are a new building type. They’re often light steel structures with what looks to the passenger like a lot of glass. But this is special glass that can maximize daylight and comfort and cut down on «energy use»«(Q40)». Bangkok's main airport is flooded with controlled daylight in a tropical climate. And this is achieved through the use of new materials and modern technology which have also allowed engineers to come up with methods of reducing costs. So let’s take a closer look at some of these...\n\nNarrator | 07:04 That is the end of part four. You now have one minute to check your answers to part four. That is the end of the listening test. In the IELTS test, you would now have 10 minutes to transfer your answers to the answer sheet.","PART 4: Self-Regulatory Focus Theory in Leadership\n\nAnnouncer | 0:09 you will hear part of a lecture about leadership introducing a theory called self-regulatory Focus Theory\n\nAnnouncer | 0:17 First you have some time to look at questions 31 to 40.\n\n(Khoảng nghỉ từ 0:20 đến 1:27)\n\nAnnouncer | 1:27 Now listen carefully and answer questions 31 to 40.\n\nLecturer | 1:35 today I want to talk about self-regulatory Focus Theory and how the actions of leaders can affect the way followers approach different situations\n\nLecturer | 1:48 self-regulatory Focus theory is a theory developed by Tory Higgins\n\nLecturer | 1:54 he says that a person's focus at any given time is to either approach pleasure or avoid pain\n\nLecturer | 2:03 these are two basic motivations that each and every one of us has and they cause us to have different kinds of goals\n\nLecturer | 2:12 promotion goals in different life situations emphasize «achievement»\n\nLecturer | 2:19 prevention goals are oriented towards the avoidance of punishment\n\nLecturer | 2:26 in a specific situation our thoughts might focus more on promotion goals or more on prevention goals\n\nLecturer | 2:36 the theory suggests that two factors affect which goals we are focusing on\n\nLecturer | 2:44 first there is a chronic Factor this factor is connected to a person's «personality» and says that each person has a basic tendency to either focus more on promotion goals or focus more on prevention goals as part of his or her personality\n\nLecturer | 3:06 second there is a «situational» factor which means that the context we are in can make us more likely to focus on one set of goals or the other\n\nLecturer | 3:19 for example we are more likely to be thinking about pleasure and to have promotion goals when we are spending time with a «friend»\n\nLecturer | 3:29 in contrast if we are working on an important project for our boss we are more likely to try to avoid making mistakes and therefore have more prevention goals in our mind\n\nLecturer | 3:46 research has shown that the goals we are focusing on at a given time affect the way we think\n\nLecturer | 3:54 for example when focusing on promotion goals people consider their ideal self their «aspirations» and gains\n\nLecturer | 4:05 they don't think about what they can lose so they think in a happier mode they feel more inspired to change\n\nLecturer | 4:15 when people are focusing on prevention goals they think about their art self what are they supposed to be what are people expecting from them\n\nLecturer | 4:27 they consider their obligations to others as a result they experience more anxiety and try to avoid situations where they could lose\n\nLecturer | 4:43 and now that I have talked about the two focuses and how they affect people I want to look at the idea that the way leaders behave or their «style» of leading can affect the focus that followers adopt in a specific situation\n\nLecturer | 5:04 in talking about leadership we often mention transformational leaders and transactional leaders\n\nLecturer | 5:13 transformational leaders when interacting with their followers focus on their «development»\n\nLecturer | 5:20 in their words and acts transformational leaders highlight change their speech is passionate and conveys a definitive «vision»\n\nLecturer | 5:33 all of these things can encourage followers to think about what could be in other words they inspire a promotion focus in their followers\n\nLecturer | 5:47 in contrast transactional leaders focus on developing clear «structures» that tell their followers exactly what is expected of them\n\nLecturer | 5:59 while they do explain the rewards people will get for following orders they emphasize more how follower will be punished or that a follower won't get rewarded if his or her behavior doesn't change\n\nLecturer | 6:15 insured they emphasize the consequences of making a mistake\n\nLecturer | 6:22 this emphasis will clearly lead followers to focus on avoiding punishment and problems this is clearly a prevention Focus\n\nLecturer | 6:34 in conclusion it is important to understand that one focus is not necessarily better than the other one\n\nLecturer | 6:43 for a designer who works in a field where a lot of «innovation» is needed a promotion focus is probably better\n\nLecturer | 6:52 in contrast a prevention Focus which causes people to work more cautiously and produce higher quality work might be very appropriate for a job Like a Surgeon for example\n\nLecturer | 7:07 the main point of the research though is that the actions of leaders can greatly influence whether people approach a situation with more of a promotion Focus or more of a prevention Focus\n\nAnnouncer | 7:26 that is the end of section four\n\nAnnouncer | 7:29 you now have half a minute to check your answers"],"listening-w8-classwork":["PART 1: Brochure Reprinting at Matrix Printing\n\nAnnouncer | 0:01 This is the IELTS listening test.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:05 You will hear a number of different recordings and you will have to answer questions on what you hear.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:12 There will be time for you to read the instructions and questions and you will have a chance to check your work.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:21 All the recordings will be played once only. The test is in four parts.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:29 At the end of the test, you will be given 10 minutes to transfer your answers to the answer sheet.\n\nAnnouncer | 0:37 Now, turn to part one. Part one,\n\nAnnouncer | 0:54 you will hear a conversation between a printing company employee and a customer. First, you have some time to look at questions 1 to five.\n\nAnnouncer | 1:30 Now we shall begin. You should answer the questions as you listen because you will not hear the recording a second time. Listen carefully and answer questions 1 to 5.\n\nJohn Smith | 1:46 Good afternoon. Welcome to Matrix Printing. I'm John Smith. How can I help you?\n\nMary Jane | 1:52 Good afternoon. I'm here to reprint a brochure for our hotel. There are some pages that need revising.\n\nJohn Smith | 2:00 Sure. How may I address you?\n\nMary Jane | 2:02 Oh, I'm Mary Jane from «Central» Hotel Chains. Nice to meet you. I've got samples of the previous version.\n\nJohn Smith | 2:10 I assume it is your company's advertising brochure. Yes. What exactly is the problem?\n\nMary Jane | 2:14 Well, it was printed the year before, so some of the information is already out of date. There are also a couple of problems with the layout. Firstly, the letters of the «address» on the front page are far too small. It's hard to see when glancing at the cover.\n\nJohn Smith | 2:30 How big do you need it to be?\n\nMary Jane | 2:35 Increase the letters by three font sizes.\n\nJohn Smith | 2:39 Just a minute. Let me take notes of your requirements. Okay. What else needs changing?\n\nMary Jane | 2:47 The information regarding the «pool» should be deleted because it is currently under renovation and is not available. So, all of the relevant descriptions on page two should be removed.\n\nJohn Smith | 2:53 What do we replace it with? We can't just leave the whole page blank.\n\nMary Jane | 3:02 Just fill it in with the introduction of our newly opened gym. I've included all the relevant information here in this flash drive.\n\nJohn Smith | 3:10 Let me check. Um, I see. No problem.\n\nMary Jane | 3:14 Then what is also bothering us is that the description under the top photos on page four is incorrect. The word lounge needs to be replaced with «reception».\n\nJohn Smith | 3:20 Fully noted. Is that all?\n\nMary Jane | 3:28 No, there is more. Turn to page five. We feel that showing merely the picture of our exterior and interior decoration does not fully represent the appeal of our hotel. On second thought, we've decided to use a picture with the «view» of the hotel.\n\nJohn Smith | 3:45 Do you have the original copy of the picture?\n\nMary Jane | 3:48 Yes, it is also enclosed in the flash drive.\n\nJohn Smith | 3:52 Okay, we'll re-edit the whole layout of the photos.\n\nMary Jane | 3:58 Great.\n\nAnnouncer | 4:00 Before you hear the rest of the conversation, you have some time to look at questions 6 to 10.\n\n4:27 Now listen and answer questions 6 to 10.\n\nJohn Smith | 4:34 Let's turn to the next page.\n\nMary Jane | 4:36 Yes.\n\nJohn Smith | 4:36 What's wrong with that? It seems perfectly fine to me.\n\nMary Jane | 4:41 At first sight, it seems fine, but according to the feedback of the customers, the «prices» do not stand out. So, we want to change the print from black to red to make it pop out.\n\nJohn Smith | 4:53 Okay. I've made notes of all of your requests. Is there anything else?\n\nMary Jane | 4:58 I appreciate it. Just one final request. Could you translate the whole brochure into «Spanish»? We have customers worldwide, you know, especially those from Latin countries.\n\nJohn Smith | 5:09 No problem. What about other languages like Japanese, Chinese or German? These are our most popular target languages.\n\nMary Jane | 5:18 I have to ask the manager about the Chinese version. There's been a surging number of Chinese clients during recent years. However, we don't need German or Japanese translations as we currently don't have many customers from those two countries.\n\nJohn Smith | 5:27 Sure, just keep me updated.\n\nMary Jane | 5:36 So, roughly, when can we get the revised print? We need it before the end of «July».\n\nJohn Smith | 5:42 It's late June now. Roughly, it will take 3 weeks to re-edit. So, it will definitely be ready before the deadline.\n\nMary Jane | 5:50 Great.\n\nJohn Smith | 5:50 To where shall we send the samples?\n\nMary Jane | 5:55 The address is number nine, Green Drive, Cliffton, NY213 O.\n\nJohn Smith | 6:00 How do you spell Clifton?\n\nMary Jane | 6:04« C L I F F T O N». Cliffton.\n\nJohn Smith | 6:09 And the telephone number?\n\nMary Jane | 6:09 It's« 903036602». Also, if you have any further questions, you can reach me through this number.\n\nJohn Smith | 6:19 Okay,\n\nAnnouncer | 6:28 that is the end of part one.\n\nAnnouncer | 6:31 You now have one minute to check your answers to part one.","PART 2: Byron National Park Introduction\n\nAnnouncer | 7:36 Part two.\n\nAnnouncer | 7:43 You will hear a guide talking to a group of visitors about a national park.\n\nAnnouncer | 7:50 First, you have some time to look at questions 11 to 16.\n\nAnnouncer | 8:26 Now listen carefully and answer questions 11 to 16.\n\nJim Carson | 8:34 Welcome to Byron National Park. I am Jim Carson, your tour guide for the trip.\n\nJim Carson | 8:40 First, I'd like to give you some basic information about the park. Covering 7,000 acres of land and spanning across three states, Byron National Park was established to protect the area's most spectacular scenic values.\n\nJim Carson | 8:58 With unique geological features, natural history, and native plant and animal life, it is an ideal destination for recreation as well as research purposes.\n\nJim Carson | 9:06 The park has a breathtaking waterfall connecting the longest river in the country, but« it is most renowned for having the largest subtropical rainforest worldwide.»\n\nJim Carson | 9:14 There are many layers of tall, medium, and low vegetation growing with seasonal variations in the park. It is a place where the air seems green.\n\nJim Carson | 9:27 Ardent hikers can find an awesome array of options here. Apart from the dense green rainforest, tourists can also hike along the mountain trail.\n\nJim Carson | 9:35 Despite the stunning view, taking photos is not advised on the way up, I'm afraid, as one might get distracted and the narrow trail by the sheer cliff is quite dangerous.\n\nJim Carson | 9:52 When you reach the top of the mountain,« there is nothing better than having a picnic under the trees with your family.»\n\nJim Carson | 9:59 Accompanied mostly by wildlife, walkers as well as cyclists may find the bush track a good choice for having a tranquil time to themselves.\n\nJim Carson | 10:10 As your tour guide,« I suggest that only expert hikers take the creek circuit» because its beautiful and inspiring scenery through the subtropical jungle is paralleled by its physical challenges.\n\nJim Carson | 10:25 A list of transport is available within the park. Bicycles are a popular choice as it is the most flexible way to get around.\n\nJim Carson | 10:33 Electric trams are temporarily closed for maintenance. Boat trips down the river are an ideal way to spend a tranquil afternoon. «Rest assured that transport within the park is covered in the bill.»\n\nJim Carson | 10:50 Extreme sports is another highlight of the park. There are for adventurous grown-ups, especially those who are comfortable with having a racing heart, scary as it may sound, it is actually safe to participate in extreme sports under strict instructions and close supervision.\n\nJim Carson | 11:10 «Abseiling»« is available regardless of the weather». It is a fun way to overcome fear of heights, gain new skills, and get an adrenaline rush. Bungee jumping and paragliding are also available except for during the summer.\n\nJim Carson | 11:27 At this point, you might worry about meals here. Well, even though there is only one restaurant in the park at the moment, the variety of dishes is astonishing.\n\nJim Carson | 11:35 There are two meals included in the price. «Just get your meal ticket at the reception before dining». Also, there is no need to make reservations or worry about availability since there are plenty of tables.\n\nAnnouncer | 11:56 Before you hear the rest of the talk, you have some time to look at questions 17 to 20.\n\nNow listen and answer questions 17 to 20.\n\nJim Carson | 12:30 During your stay here, you might want to know what there is to do. Let's turn to the plan so I can familiarize you with the layout of the park.\n\nJim Carson | 12:38 «Most tourists would choose to stay in our guest house located in the southeast corner.» It features 63 tastefully appointed guest rooms, many of which offer spectacular views of the park. You'll find a home away from home at our guest house.\n\nJim Carson | 12:59 But for those who want to experience the natural beauty up close, there is also a «campsite».\n\nJim Carson | 13:05« When you get out of the guest house, go straight ahead. Turn right at the end of the road.» To your left, there is a campsite amongst the trees where you could spend a night under the stars together with owls and chipmunks.\n\nJim Carson | 13:20 If you look at the top left of the plan, you will notice a picnic area. You can either bring your own food or we can deliver food to you. Barbecue is an option.\n\nJim Carson | 13:31 «The business center is situated directly opposite the picnic area». It provides flexible fully serviced offices, conferencing suites, meeting rooms and is equipped with the latest multimedia facilities.\n\nJim Carson | 13:47 Wired as well as wireless high-speed internet is available within the entire premises. The center is designed to cater to both individual travelers and corporate groups.\n\nJim Carson | 14:00 Visitors can also go to the museum which holds a vast collection that exhibits local history and a natural habitat.\n\nJim Carson | 14:06 «You start from the guest house, just turn left at the first conjunction, then walk past the tea house. Turn right, you'll see the museum after making the third right.» Have you found it pretty easy, right?\n\nJim Carson | 14:26 To spend a delightful afternoon with a book and a fresh cup of coffee, you can go to the only cafe in the park.\n\nJim Carson | 14:33« From the guest house, you go straight, then take the second right, and you'll see the cafe right in front of you.»\n\nJim Carson | 14:42 You might want to check out our all-season tennis court, which offers instruction for all ages and skill levels. It is located right opposite the cafe.\n\nAnnouncer | 14:58 That is the end of part two.\n\nAnnouncer | 15:01 You now have 30 seconds to check your answers to part two.","PART 3: Nursing Course Feedback\n\nAnnouncer | 15:35 part three.\n\nAnnouncer | 15:42 You will hear two students called Helen and Paul talking to their tutor about a nursing course. First, you have some time to look at questions 21 to 24.\n\nNow listen carefully and answer questions 21 to 24.\n\nTutor | 16:34 Helen and Paul, congratulations to you both for doing so well the past semester. You two have exhibited an impeccable performance during your first year in the nursing program.\n\nTutor | 16:41 I'd like to get some feedback from the two of you to better improve the program and to provide guidance for our prospective students. I'd like to start with you, Helen. So, first of all, which aspect of the program impressed you?\n\nHelen | 16:54 Well, to be honest, when I was enrolled into the course, I was expecting a group of classmates my age. But as I stepped into the classroom for the first time, I was surprised by the diversity.\n\nHelen | 17:10 Most were in their 20s, but there were also those in their 30s or even 40s. As it turns out, the intergenerational communication has sparked intense debate and new thinking, and I think that's something special about the program that I appreciate very much.\n\nTutor | 17:28 What about you, Paul? What do you think of the program?\n\nPaul | 17:31 For me, the group project we carried out last semester is another key feature of the program. The whole class was divided into eight different groups working on eight prospective cases. Team building sessions were conducted in a collaborative way.\n\nPaul | 17:49 Most of the time consisted of five members, our group studied acute pancreatitis. During the process, we broke the task into different parts and assigned them to each member.\n\nPaul | 18:02 We were then able to tackle the complex problem by pulling our knowledge and skills. More importantly, stronger links were established between the group members. Because of the project, we've all become good friends.\n\nTutor | 18:11 That's true. According to graduates, group projects prepare them for the work world in which teamwork and collaboration are increasingly the norm. So tell me Paul, what else do you like about the program?\n\nPaul | 18:27 I want to be a registered nurse working in a public hospital after graduation. So the internship provided is a valuable opportunity for clinical practice in a supportive learning atmosphere.\n\nPaul | 18:40 However, I was amazed by the amount of written assignments since I thought the course should have focused more on practice-oriented learning.\n\nHelen | 18:49 Well, I have to disagree with you, Paul. The essays demonstrate your understanding of the course. For me, writing essays is a process that involves critical thinking, which challenges me to develop my points more thoroughly. I thus managed to gain a diversity of perspectives.\n\nTutor | 19:03 The program is designed to deliver basic and advanced theoretical knowledge of core concepts including health care systems concepts together with practicum or clinical practice experience to bridge the classroom content to the practice setting.\n\nTutor | 19:19 So I'm afraid written work is unavoidable. Also this year we've added a module of law. How do you feel about that?\n\nHelen | 19:27 At first we felt that learning law was kind of redundant and too time consuming. After a few sessions we realized that it is necessary in dealing with future medical disputes.\n\nAnnouncer | 19:45 Before you hear the rest of the talk, you have some time to look at questions 25 to 30.\n\nNow listen and answer questions 25 to 30.\n\nTutor | 20:20 Do you have any suggestions for prospective students?\n\nPaul | 20:20 What bothers me most is handing in essays on time. I almost missed the deadline once because there were three essays due within the same week. So rationalizing your time is critical.\n\nHelen | 20:36 Well, that's true. The lectures deliver so much useful information. I have poor memory, so I kept making notes and revisiting them on a regular basis. To my surprise, at the end of the semester, I have learned the key concepts by heart.\n\nTutor | 20:51 How was the research? I heard that it was quite challenging. How did you manage to overcome the difficulties?\n\nPaul | 20:57 That's true. The majority of us had no clue how to carry out the research at first. Fortunately, when I was digging up reference materials at the library, I sought help from the librarian.\n\nPaul | 21:04 She taught me about finding the appropriate resources and choosing the proper research methods.\n\nTutor | 21:12 Have you checked out the online forum?\n\nHelen | 21:17 Yes, it has become a habit for me to visit the forum regularly. In a sense, it extends classroom learning. It is where the students post academic problems that they come across and get support from the faculty members.\n\nPaul | 21:30 Some of my classmates didn't do so well during the placement tests. I feel that background reading is necessary.\n\nTutor | 21:38 Lastly, do you have anything to say to the freshmen?\n\nPaul | 21:41 I was really ambitious at first trying to get straight A's on my transcript. I made tons of notes and worked hard, even on the optional assignments, to get extra credit. I stressed myself out before having an emotional breakdown.\n\nPaul | 21:56 After consulting my advisor, I found it important to set realistic goals. Don't push yourself too hard. It is wise to sort out your priorities.\n\nTutor | 22:06 Thank you for coming here today and providing valuable feedback on the program. Have a great summer break.\n\nAnnouncer | 22:16 That is the end of part three.\n\nAnnouncer | 22:20 You now have 30 seconds to check your answers to part three.","PART 4: African Penguins Lecture\n\nAnnouncer | 22:54 Part four.\n\nAnnouncer | 23:00 You will hear part of a lecture about African penguins. First, you have some time to look at questions 31 to 40.\n\nAnnouncer | 23:50 Now listen carefully and answer questions 31 to 40.\n\nLecturer | 23:57 Good morning everyone. Today's lecture is about a type of adorable animal, the penguin. When you think of penguins, you may picture them surrounded by snow and ice.\n\nLecturer | 24:06 But not all penguins live where it's cold. African penguins live in the southern tip of Africa. They are usually found within 40 km of the shore and on a number of its surrounding islands.\n\nLecturer | 24:21 African penguins are also known as jackass penguins because they make donkey-like preying sounds to communicate.\n\nLecturer | 24:28 African penguins can keep their body temperature at a stable level, but their land habitat can get quite warm. So, there are a number of ways for them to stay cool.\n\nLecturer | 24:35 They limit their daylight movements on breeding sites on land to early mornings and early evenings to avoid too much sun. The pink glands above their eyes can help them cope with the temperate climates.\n\nLecturer | 24:48 Like other penguins, African penguins spend most of the day feeding in the ocean, which also helps keep them cool.\n\nLecturer | 24:57 Being a type of small to medium-sized penguin species, African penguins average about 60 cm tall and weigh up to 3.6 kg. They have a black stripe and a pattern of unique black spots on their chest.\n\nLecturer | 25:13 Males are larger than females and have larger beaks. Even though they are categorized as birds, African penguins aren't able to fly because of their heavy bones.\n\nLecturer | 25:20 Their wings are more like flippers that make them particularly suited for life in the water. When they're on land, their flippers and their tails help them keep their balance and walk upright.\n\nLecturer | 25:36 African penguins begin to breed at the average age of four. When a male and female pair up, they tend to breed together for the rest of their lives. Most other penguins nest and lay their eggs out in the open.\n\nLecturer | 25:48 But African penguins have a different approach. They dig holes under bushes out of their own excrement called guano. So they are sheltered from the sun and predators.\n\nLecturer | 25:57 The African penguins survive on a diet that is composed mainly of marine organisms. They feed primarily on fish like sardines along with the occasional squid and shellfish.\n\nLecturer | 26:12 But when normal food is in short supply, they eat tree roots as well.\n\nLecturer | 26:15 The streamlined body of the African penguin allows it to move through the water like a rocket, capable of reaching a speed of around 20 kmh when hunting for food.\n\nLecturer | 26:31 The African penguin's smaller size means that it has many predators both in the water and also on dry land. Their natural predators at sea include seals and sharks.\n\nLecturer | 26:40 The biggest threat to them on land is not just towards the adult penguins. The penguin chicks are sometimes taken by seagulls into the air and dropped from above. The seagulls could thus feed on them.\n\nLecturer | 26:55 At risk from predators, young penguins are protected for about 40 days after hatching by both parents. They will leave the colony when they are between 3 to 5 months old and will return a few years later.\n\nLecturer | 27:09 The entire surface of their body is densely covered with feathers which fall off during the winter. This process is called molting and takes about 3 weeks to complete.\n\nLecturer | 27:16 During that time, they are unable to forage. Therefore, prior to this, African penguins spend about 5 weeks laying down fat deposits. They generally live between 10 to 15 years.\n\nLecturer | 27:33 However, many do not reach their full lifespan. Their population has drastically declined. Approximately 120,000 African penguins remain in the wild and their population has decreased by 90% in the past 60 years.\n\nLecturer | 27:50 They are considered to be vulnerable and have been listed as being endangered. Two major factors have contributed to their decline.\n\nLecturer | 27:59 They are struggling for nesting space due to human disruption and competing for food due to over fishing and pollution. With the limited number of breeding pairs, survivorship becomes difficult for African penguins.\n\nLecturer | 28:07 This makes them especially vulnerable as environmental conditions change or an outbreak of a disease occurs.\n\nLecturer | 28:15 For instance, malaria has caused 27% of the captive breeding penguins' deaths annually.\n\nLecturer | 28:24 The more genetic diversity there is within a species, the higher the likelihood that at least some of the individuals will adapt and survive.\n\nAnnouncer | 28:40 That is the end of part four.\n\nAnnouncer | 28:43 You now have one minute to check your answers to part four.\n\nAnnouncer | 28:50 That is the end of the listening test.\n\nAnnouncer | 28:54 In the IELTS test, you would now have 10 minutes to transfer your answers to the answer sheet."]};
